U||O my soul, I taught thee so to persuade that thou persuadest even the grounds themselves to thee: like the sun, which persuadeth even the sea to its height.
U||O my soul, I have taken from thee all obeying and knee-bending and homage-paying; I have myself given thee the names, ‚ÄúChange of need‚Äù and ‚ÄúFate.‚Äù
U||O my soul, I have given thee new names and gay-coloured playthings, I have called thee ‚ÄúFate‚Äù and ‚Äúthe Circuit of circuits‚Äù and ‚Äúthe Navel-string of time‚Äù and ‚Äúthe Azure bell.‚Äù
U||O my soul, to thy domain gave I all wisdom to drink, all new wines, and also all immemorially old strong wines of wisdom.
U||O my soul, every sun shed I upon thee, and every night and every silence and every longing:‚Äîthen grewest thou up for me as a vine.
U||O my soul, exuberant and heavy dost thou now stand forth, a vine with swelling udders and full clusters of brown golden grapes:‚Äî
U||‚ÄîFilled and weighted by thy happiness, waiting from superabundance, and yet ashamed of thy waiting.
U||O my soul, there is nowhere a soul which could be more loving and more comprehensive and more extensive! Where could future and past be closer together than with thee?
U||O my soul, I have given thee everything, and all my hands have become empty by thee:‚Äîand now! Now sayest thou to me, smiling and full of melancholy: ‚ÄúWhich of us oweth thanks?‚Äî
U||‚ÄîDoth the giver not owe thanks because the receiver received? Is bestowing not a necessity? Is receiving not‚Äîpitying?‚Äù‚Äî
U||O my soul, I understand the smiling of thy melancholy: thine over-abundance itself now stretcheth out longing hands!
U||Thy fulness looketh forth over raging seas, and seeketh and waiteth: the longing of over-fulness looketh forth from the smiling heaven of thine eyes!
U||And verily, O my soul! Who could see thy smiling and not melt into tears? The angels themselves melt into tears through the over-graciousness of thy smiling.
U||Thy graciousness and over-graciousness, is it which will not complain and weep: and yet, O my soul, longeth thy smiling for tears, and thy trembling mouth for sobs.
U||‚ÄúIs not all weeping complaining? And all complaining, accusing?‚Äù Thus speakest thou to thyself; and therefore, O my soul, wilt thou rather smile than pour forth thy grief‚Äî
