U||My heels reared aloft, my toes they hearkened,‚Äîthee they would know: hath not the dancer his ear‚Äîin his toe!
U||Unto thee did I spring: then fledst thou back from my bound; and towards me waved thy fleeing, flying tresses round!
U||Away from thee did I spring, and from thy snaky tresses: then stoodst thou there half-turned, and in thine eye caresses.
U||With crooked glances‚Äîdost thou teach me crooked courses; on crooked courses learn my feet‚Äîcrafty fancies!
U||I fear thee near, I love thee far; thy flight allureth me, thy seeking secureth me:‚ÄîI suffer, but for thee, what would I not gladly bear!
