U||I dance after thee, I follow even faint traces lonely. Where art thou? Give me thy hand! Or thy finger only!
U||Here are caves and thickets: we shall go astray!‚ÄîHalt! Stand still! Seest thou not owls and bats in fluttering fray?
U||Thou bat! Thou owl! Thou wouldst play me foul? Where are we? From the dogs hast thou learned thus to bark and howl.
U||Thou gnashest on me sweetly with little white teeth; thine evil eyes shoot out upon me, thy curly little mane from underneath!
U||This is a dance over stock and stone: I am the hunter,‚Äîwilt thou be my hound, or my chamois anon?
U||Now beside me! And quickly, wickedly springing! Now up! And over!‚ÄîAlas! I have fallen myself overswinging!
U||Oh, see me lying, thou arrogant one, and imploring grace! Gladly would I walk with thee‚Äîin some lovelier place!
