U||LXXVII. THE AWAKENING.
U||1.
U||After the song of the wanderer and shadow, the cave became all at once full of noise and laughter: and since the assembled guests all spake simultaneously, and even the ass, encouraged thereby, no longer remained silent, a little aversion and scorn for his visitors came over Zarathustra, although he rejoiced at their gladness. For it seemed to him a sign of convalescence. So he slipped out into the open air and spake to his animals.
U||‚ÄúWhither hath their distress now gone?‚Äù said he, and already did he himself feel relieved of his petty disgust‚Äî‚Äúwith me, it seemeth that they have unlearned their cries of distress!
U||‚ÄîThough, alas! not yet their crying.‚Äù And Zarathustra stopped his ears, for just then did the YE-A of the ass mix strangely with the noisy jubilation of those higher men.
U||‚ÄúThey are merry,‚Äù he began again, ‚Äúand who knoweth? perhaps at their host‚Äôs expense; and if they have learned of me to laugh, still it is not MY laughter they have learned.
U||But what matter about that! They are old people: they recover in their own way, they laugh in their own way; mine ears have already endured worse and have not become peevish.
U||This day is a victory: he already yieldeth, he fleeth, THE SPIRIT OF GRAVITY, mine old arch-enemy! How well this day is about to end, which began so badly and gloomily!
U||And it is ABOUT TO end. Already cometh the evening: over the sea rideth it hither, the good rider! How it bobbeth, the blessed one, the home-returning one, in its purple saddles!
U||The sky gazeth brightly thereon, the world lieth deep. Oh, all ye strange ones who have come to me, it is already worth while to have lived with me!‚Äù
U||Thus spake Zarathustra. And again came the cries and laughter of the higher men out of the cave: then began he anew:
U||‚ÄúThey bite at it, my bait taketh, there departeth also from them their enemy, the spirit of gravity. Now do they learn to laugh at themselves: do I hear rightly?
U||My virile food taketh effect, my strong and savoury sayings: and verily, I did not nourish them with flatulent vegetables! But with warrior-food, with conqueror-food: new desires did I awaken.
U||New hopes are in their arms and legs, their hearts expand. They find new words, soon will their spirits breathe wantonness.
U||Such food may sure enough not be proper for children, nor even for longing girls old and young. One persuadeth their bowels otherwise; I am not their physician and teacher.
U||The DISGUST departeth from these higher men; well! that is my victory. In my domain they become assured; all stupid shame fleeth away; they empty themselves.
U||They empty their hearts, good times return unto them, they keep holiday and ruminate,‚Äîthey become THANKFUL.
U||THAT do I take as the best sign: they become thankful. Not long will it be ere they devise festivals, and put up memorials to their old joys.
U||They are CONVALESCENTS!‚Äù Thus spake Zarathustra joyfully to his heart and gazed outward; his animals, however, pressed up to him, and honoured his happiness and his silence.
U||2.
U||All on a sudden however, Zarathustra‚Äôs ear was frightened: for the cave which had hitherto been full of noise and laughter, became all at once still as death;‚Äîhis nose, however, smelt a sweet-scented vapour and incense-odour, as if from burning pine-cones.
U||‚ÄúWhat happeneth? What are they about?‚Äù he asked himself, and stole up to the entrance, that he might be able unobserved to see his guests. But wonder upon wonder! what was he then obliged to behold with his own eyes!
U||‚ÄúThey have all of them become PIOUS again, they PRAY, they are mad!‚Äù‚Äîsaid he, and was astonished beyond measure. And forsooth! all these higher men, the two kings, the pope out of service, the evil magician, the voluntary beggar, the wanderer and shadow, the old soothsayer, the spiritually conscientious one, and the ugliest man‚Äîthey all lay on their knees like children and credulous old women, and worshipped the ass. And just then began the ugliest man to gurgle and snort, as if something unutterable in him tried to find expression; when, however, he had actually found words, behold! it was a pious, strange litany in praise of the adored and censed ass. And the litany sounded thus:
U||Amen! And glory and honour and wisdom and thanks and praise and strength be to our God, from everlasting to everlasting!
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||He carrieth our burdens, he hath taken upon him the form of a servant, he is patient of heart and never saith Nay; and he who loveth his God chastiseth him.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||He speaketh not: except that he ever saith Yea to the world which he created: thus doth he extol his world. It is his artfulness that speaketh not: thus is he rarely found wrong.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||Uncomely goeth he through the world. Grey is the favourite colour in which he wrappeth his virtue. Hath he spirit, then doth he conceal it; every one, however, believeth in his long ears.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||What hidden wisdom it is to wear long ears, and only to say Yea and never Nay! Hath he not created the world in his own image, namely, as stupid as possible?
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||Thou goest straight and crooked ways; it concerneth thee little what seemeth straight or crooked unto us men. Beyond good and evil is thy domain. It is thine innocence not to know what innocence is.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||Lo! how thou spurnest none from thee, neither beggars nor kings. Thou sufferest little children to come unto thee, and when the bad boys decoy thee, then sayest thou simply, YE-A.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||Thou lovest she-asses and fresh figs, thou art no food-despiser. A thistle tickleth thy heart when thou chancest to be hungry. There is the wisdom of a God therein.
U||‚ÄîThe ass, however, here brayed YE-A.
U||LXXVIII. THE ASS-FESTIVAL.
U||1.
U||At this place in the litany, however, Zarathustra could no longer control himself; he himself cried out YE-A, louder even than the ass, and sprang into the midst of his maddened guests. ‚ÄúWhatever are you about, ye grown-up children?‚Äù he exclaimed, pulling up the praying ones from the ground. ‚ÄúAlas, if any one else, except Zarathustra, had seen you:
U||Every one would think you the worst blasphemers, or the very foolishest old women, with your new belief!
U||And thou thyself, thou old pope, how is it in accordance with thee, to adore an ass in such a manner as God?‚Äù‚Äî
U||‚ÄúO Zarathustra,‚Äù answered the pope, ‚Äúforgive me, but in divine matters I am more enlightened even than thou. And it is right that it should be so.
U||Better to adore God so, in this form, than in no form at all! Think over this saying, mine exalted friend: thou wilt readily divine that in such a saying there is wisdom.
U||He who said ‚ÄòGod is a Spirit‚Äô‚Äîmade the greatest stride and slide hitherto made on earth towards unbelief: such a dictum is not easily amended again on earth!
U||Mine old heart leapeth and boundeth because there is still something to adore on earth. Forgive it, O Zarathustra, to an old, pious pontiff-heart!‚Äî‚Äù
U||‚Äî‚ÄúAnd thou,‚Äù said Zarathustra to the wanderer and shadow, ‚Äúthou callest and thinkest thyself a free spirit? And thou here practisest such idolatry and hierolatry?
U||Worse verily, doest thou here than with thy bad brown girls, thou bad, new believer!‚Äù
U||‚ÄúIt is sad enough,‚Äù answered the wanderer and shadow, ‚Äúthou art right: but how can I help it! The old God liveth again, O Zarathustra, thou mayst say what thou wilt.
U||The ugliest man is to blame for it all: he hath reawakened him. And if he say that he once killed him, with Gods DEATH is always just a prejudice.‚Äù
U||‚Äî‚ÄúAnd thou,‚Äù said Zarathustra, ‚Äúthou bad old magician, what didst thou do! Who ought to believe any longer in thee in this free age, when THOU believest in such divine donkeyism?
U||It was a stupid thing that thou didst; how couldst thou, a shrewd man, do such a stupid thing!‚Äù
U||‚ÄúO Zarathustra,‚Äù answered the shrewd magician, ‚Äúthou art right, it was a stupid thing,‚Äîit was also repugnant to me.‚Äù
U||‚Äî‚ÄúAnd thou even,‚Äù said Zarathustra to the spiritually conscientious one, ‚Äúconsider, and put thy finger to thy nose! Doth nothing go against thy conscience here? Is thy spirit not too cleanly for this praying and the fumes of those devotees?‚Äù
U||‚ÄúThere is something therein,‚Äù said the spiritually conscientious one, and put his finger to his nose, ‚Äúthere is something in this spectacle which even doeth good to my conscience.
U||Perhaps I dare not believe in God: certain it is however, that God seemeth to me most worthy of belief in this form.
U||God is said to be eternal, according to the testimony of the most pious: he who hath so much time taketh his time. As slow and as stupid as possible: THEREBY can such a one nevertheless go very far.
U||And he who hath too much spirit might well become infatuated with stupidity and folly. Think of thyself, O Zarathustra!
U||Thou thyself‚Äîverily! even thou couldst well become an ass through superabundance of wisdom.
U||Doth not the true sage willingly walk on the crookedest paths? The evidence teacheth it, O Zarathustra,‚ÄîTHINE OWN evidence!‚Äù
U||‚Äî‚ÄúAnd thou thyself, finally,‚Äù said Zarathustra, and turned towards the ugliest man, who still lay on the ground stretching up his arm to the ass (for he gave it wine to drink). ‚ÄúSay, thou nondescript, what hast thou been about!
U||Thou seemest to me transformed, thine eyes glow, the mantle of the sublime covereth thine ugliness: WHAT didst thou do?
U||Is it then true what they say, that thou hast again awakened him? And why? Was he not for good reasons killed and made away with?
U||Thou thyself seemest to me awakened: what didst thou do? why didst THOU turn round? Why didst THOU get converted? Speak, thou nondescript!‚Äù
U||‚ÄúO Zarathustra,‚Äù answered the ugliest man, ‚Äúthou art a rogue!
U||Whether HE yet liveth, or again liveth, or is thoroughly dead‚Äîwhich of us both knoweth that best? I ask thee.
U||One thing however do I know,‚Äîfrom thyself did I learn it once, O Zarathustra: he who wanteth to kill most thoroughly, LAUGHETH.
U||‚ÄòNot by wrath but by laughter doth one kill‚Äô‚Äîthus spakest thou once, O Zarathustra, thou hidden one, thou destroyer without wrath, thou dangerous saint,‚Äîthou art a rogue!‚Äù
U||2.
U||Then, however, did it come to pass that Zarathustra, astonished at such merely roguish answers, jumped back to the door of his cave, and turning towards all his guests, cried out with a strong voice:
U||‚ÄúO ye wags, all of you, ye buffoons! Why do ye dissemble and disguise yourselves before me!
U||How the hearts of all of you convulsed with delight and wickedness, because ye had at last become again like little children‚Äînamely, pious,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîBecause ye at last did again as children do‚Äînamely, prayed, folded your hands and said ‚Äògood God‚Äô!
U||But now leave, I pray you, THIS nursery, mine own cave, where to-day all childishness is carried on. Cool down, here outside, your hot child-wantonness and heart-tumult!
U||To be sure: except ye become as little children ye shall not enter into THAT kingdom of heaven.‚Äù (And Zarathustra pointed aloft with his hands.)
U||‚ÄúBut we do not at all want to enter into the kingdom of heaven: we have become men,‚ÄîSO WE WANT THE KINGDOM OF EARTH.‚Äù
U||3.
U||And once more began Zarathustra to speak. ‚ÄúO my new friends,‚Äù said he,‚Äî ‚Äúye strange ones, ye higher men, how well do ye now please me,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîSince ye have again become joyful! Ye have, verily, all blossomed forth: it seemeth to me that for such flowers as you, NEW FESTIVALS are required.
U||‚ÄîA little valiant nonsense, some divine service and ass-festival, some old joyful Zarathustra fool, some blusterer to blow your souls bright.
U||Forget not this night and this ass-festival, ye higher men! THAT did ye devise when with me, that do I take as a good omen,‚Äîsuch things only the convalescents devise!
U||And should ye celebrate it again, this ass-festival, do it from love to yourselves, do it also from love to me! And in remembrance of me!‚Äù
U||Thus spake Zarathustra.
U||LXXIX. THE DRUNKEN SONG.
U||1.
U||Meanwhile one after another had gone out into the open air, and into the cool, thoughtful night; Zarathustra himself, however, led the ugliest man by the hand, that he might show him his night-world, and the great round moon, and the silvery water-falls near his cave. There they at last stood still beside one another; all of them old people, but with comforted, brave hearts, and astonished in themselves that it was so well with them on earth; the mystery of the night, however, came nigher and nigher to their hearts. And anew Zarathustra thought to himself: ‚ÄúOh, how well do they now please me, these higher men!‚Äù‚Äîbut he did not say it aloud, for he respected their happiness and their silence.‚Äî
U||Then, however, there happened that which in this astonishing long day was most astonishing: the ugliest man began once more and for the last time to gurgle and snort, and when he had at length found expression, behold! there sprang a question plump and plain out of his mouth, a good, deep, clear question, which moved the hearts of all who listened to him.
U||‚ÄúMy friends, all of you,‚Äù said the ugliest man, ‚Äúwhat think ye? For the sake of this day‚ÄîI am for the first time content to have lived mine entire life.
U||And that I testify so much is still not enough for me. It is worth while living on the earth: one day, one festival with Zarathustra, hath taught me to love the earth.
U||‚ÄòWas THAT‚Äîlife?‚Äô will I say unto death. ‚ÄòWell! Once more!‚Äô
U||My friends, what think ye? Will ye not, like me, say unto death: ‚ÄòWas THAT‚Äîlife? For the sake of Zarathustra, well! Once more!‚Äô‚Äù‚Äî
U||Thus spake the ugliest man; it was not, however, far from midnight. And what took place then, think ye? As soon as the higher men heard his question, they became all at once conscious of their transformation and convalescence, and of him who was the cause thereof: then did they rush up to Zarathustra, thanking, honouring, caressing him, and kissing his hands, each in his own peculiar way; so that some laughed and some wept. The old soothsayer, however, danced with delight; and though he was then, as some narrators suppose, full of sweet wine, he was certainly still fuller of sweet life, and had renounced all weariness. There are even those who narrate that the ass then danced: for not in vain had the ugliest man previously given it wine to drink. That may be the case, or it may be otherwise; and if in truth the ass did not dance that evening, there nevertheless happened then greater and rarer wonders than the dancing of an ass would have been. In short, as the proverb of Zarathustra saith: ‚ÄúWhat doth it ma
U||tter!‚Äù
U||2.
U||When, however, this took place with the ugliest man, Zarathustra stood there like one drunken: his glance dulled, his tongue faltered and his feet staggered. And who could divine what thoughts then passed through Zarathustra‚Äôs soul? Apparently, however, his spirit retreated and fled in advance and was in remote distances, and as it were ‚Äúwandering on high mountain-ridges,‚Äù as it standeth written, ‚Äú‚Äòtwixt two seas,
U||‚ÄîWandering ‚Äòtwixt the past and the future as a heavy cloud.‚Äù Gradually, however, while the higher men held him in their arms, he came back to himself a little, and resisted with his hands the crowd of the honouring and caring ones; but he did not speak. All at once, however, he turned his head quickly, for he seemed to hear something: then laid he his finger on his mouth and said: ‚ÄúCOME!‚Äù
U||And immediately it became still and mysterious round about; from the depth however there came up slowly the sound of a clock-bell. Zarathustra listened thereto, like the higher men; then, however, laid he his finger on his mouth the second time, and said again: ‚ÄúCOME! COME! IT IS GETTING ON TO MIDNIGHT!‚Äù‚Äîand his voice had changed. But still he had not moved from the spot. Then it became yet stiller and more mysterious, and everything hearkened, even the ass, and Zarathustra‚Äôs noble animals, the eagle and the serpent,‚Äîlikewise the cave of Zarathustra and the big cool moon, and the night itself. Zarathustra, however, laid his hand upon his mouth for the third time, and said:
U||COME! COME! COME! LET US NOW WANDER! IT IS THE HOUR: LET US WANDER INTO THE NIGHT!
U||3.
U||Ye higher men, it is getting on to midnight: then will I say something into your ears, as that old clock-bell saith it into mine ear,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîAs mysteriously, as frightfully, and as cordially as that midnight clock-bell speaketh it to me, which hath experienced more than one man:
U||‚ÄîWhich hath already counted the smarting throbbings of your fathers‚Äô hearts‚Äîah! ah! how it sigheth! how it laugheth in its dream! the old, deep, deep midnight!
U||Hush! Hush! Then is there many a thing heard which may not be heard by day; now however, in the cool air, when even all the tumult of your hearts hath become still,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîNow doth it speak, now is it heard, now doth it steal into overwakeful, nocturnal souls: ah! ah! how the midnight sigheth! how it laugheth in its dream!
U||‚ÄîHearest thou not how it mysteriously, frightfully, and cordially speaketh unto THEE, the old deep, deep midnight?
U||O MAN, TAKE HEED! 4.
U||Woe to me! Whither hath time gone? Have I not sunk into deep wells? The world sleepeth‚Äî
U||Ah! Ah! The dog howleth, the moon shineth. Rather will I die, rather will I die, than say unto you what my midnight-heart now thinketh.
U||Already have I died. It is all over. Spider, why spinnest thou around me? Wilt thou have blood? Ah! Ah! The dew falleth, the hour cometh‚Äî
U||‚ÄîThe hour in which I frost and freeze, which asketh and asketh and asketh: ‚ÄúWho hath sufficient courage for it?
U||‚ÄîWho is to be master of the world? Who is going to say: THUS shall ye flow, ye great and small streams!‚Äù
U||‚ÄîThe hour approacheth: O man, thou higher man, take heed! this talk is for fine ears, for thine ears‚ÄîWHAT SAITH DEEP MIDNIGHT‚ÄôS VOICE INDEED?
U||5.
U||It carrieth me away, my soul danceth. Day‚Äôs-work! Day‚Äôs-work! Who is to be master of the world?
U||The moon is cool, the wind is still. Ah! Ah! Have ye already flown high enough? Ye have danced: a leg, nevertheless, is not a wing.
U||Ye good dancers, now is all delight over: wine hath become lees, every cup hath become brittle, the sepulchres mutter.
U||Ye have not flown high enough: now do the sepulchres mutter: ‚ÄúFree the dead! Why is it so long night? Doth not the moon make us drunken?‚Äù
U||Ye higher men, free the sepulchres, awaken the corpses! Ah, why doth the worm still burrow? There approacheth, there approacheth, the hour,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîThere boometh the clock-bell, there thrilleth still the heart, there burroweth still the wood-worm, the heart-worm. Ah! Ah! THE WORLD IS DEEP!
U||6.
U||Sweet lyre! Sweet lyre! I love thy tone, thy drunken, ranunculine tone!‚Äîhow long, how far hath come unto me thy tone, from the distance, from the ponds of love!
U||Thou old clock-bell, thou sweet lyre! Every pain hath torn thy heart, father-pain, fathers‚Äô-pain, forefathers‚Äô-pain; thy speech hath become ripe,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîRipe like the golden autumn and the afternoon, like mine anchorite heart‚Äînow sayest thou: The world itself hath become ripe, the grape turneth brown,
U||‚ÄîNow doth it wish to die, to die of happiness. Ye higher men, do ye not feel it? There welleth up mysteriously an odour,
U||‚ÄîA perfume and odour of eternity, a rosy-blessed, brown, gold-wine-odour of old happiness,
U||‚ÄîOf drunken midnight-death happiness, which singeth: the world is deep, AND DEEPER THAN THE DAY COULD READ!
U||7.
U||Leave me alone! Leave me alone! I am too pure for thee. Touch me not! Hath not my world just now become perfect?
U||My skin is too pure for thy hands. Leave me alone, thou dull, doltish, stupid day! Is not the midnight brighter?
U||The purest are to be masters of the world, the least known, the strongest, the midnight-souls, who are brighter and deeper than any day.
U||O day, thou gropest for me? Thou feelest for my happiness? For thee am I rich, lonesome, a treasure-pit, a gold chamber?
U||O world, thou wantest ME? Am I worldly for thee? Am I spiritual for thee? Am I divine for thee? But day and world, ye are too coarse,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîHave cleverer hands, grasp after deeper happiness, after deeper unhappiness, grasp after some God; grasp not after me:
U||‚ÄîMine unhappiness, my happiness is deep, thou strange day, but yet am I no God, no God‚Äôs-hell: DEEP IS ITS WOE.
U||8.
U||God‚Äôs woe is deeper, thou strange world! Grasp at God‚Äôs woe, not at me! What am I! A drunken sweet lyre,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîA midnight-lyre, a bell-frog, which no one understandeth, but which MUST speak before deaf ones, ye higher men! For ye do not understand me!
U||Gone! Gone! O youth! O noontide! O afternoon! Now have come evening and night and midnight,‚Äîthe dog howleth, the wind:
U||‚ÄîIs the wind not a dog? It whineth, it barketh, it howleth. Ah! Ah! how she sigheth! how she laugheth, how she wheezeth and panteth, the midnight!
U||How she just now speaketh soberly, this drunken poetess! hath she perhaps overdrunk her drunkenness? hath she become overawake? doth she ruminate?
U||‚ÄîHer woe doth she ruminate over, in a dream, the old, deep midnight‚Äîand still more her joy. For joy, although woe be deep, JOY IS DEEPER STILL THAN GRIEF CAN BE.
U||9.
U||Thou grape-vine! Why dost thou praise me? Have I not cut thee! I am cruel, thou bleedest‚Äî: what meaneth thy praise of my drunken cruelty?
U||‚ÄúWhatever hath become perfect, everything mature‚Äîwanteth to die!‚Äù so sayest thou. Blessed, blessed be the vintner‚Äôs knife! But everything immature wanteth to live: alas!
U||Woe saith: ‚ÄúHence! Go! Away, thou woe!‚Äù But everything that suffereth wanteth to live, that it may become mature and lively and longing,
U||‚ÄîLonging for the further, the higher, the brighter. ‚ÄúI want heirs,‚Äù so saith everything that suffereth, ‚ÄúI want children, I do not want MYSELF,‚Äù‚Äî
U||Joy, however, doth not want heirs, it doth not want children,‚Äîjoy wanteth itself, it wanteth eternity, it wanteth recurrence, it wanteth everything eternally-like-itself.
U||Woe saith: ‚ÄúBreak, bleed, thou heart! Wander, thou leg! Thou wing, fly! Onward! upward! thou pain!‚Äù Well! Cheer up! O mine old heart: WOE SAITH: ‚ÄúHENCE! GO!‚Äù
U||10.
U||Ye higher men, what think ye? Am I a soothsayer? Or a dreamer? Or a drunkard? Or a dream-reader? Or a midnight-bell?
U||Or a drop of dew? Or a fume and fragrance of eternity? Hear ye it not? Smell ye it not? Just now hath my world become perfect, midnight is also midday,‚Äî
U||Pain is also a joy, curse is also a blessing, night is also a sun,‚Äîgo away! or ye will learn that a sage is also a fool.
U||Said ye ever Yea to one joy? O my friends, then said ye Yea also unto ALL woe. All things are enlinked, enlaced and enamoured,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîWanted ye ever once to come twice; said ye ever: ‚ÄúThou pleasest me, happiness! Instant! Moment!‚Äù then wanted ye ALL to come back again!
U||‚ÄîAll anew, all eternal, all enlinked, enlaced and enamoured, Oh, then did ye LOVE the world,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîYe eternal ones, ye love it eternally and for all time: and also unto woe do ye say: Hence! Go! but come back! FOR JOYS ALL WANT‚ÄîETERNITY!
U||11.
U||All joy wanteth the eternity of all things, it wanteth honey, it wanteth lees, it wanteth drunken midnight, it wanteth graves, it wanteth grave-tears‚Äô consolation, it wanteth gilded evening-red‚Äî
U||‚ÄîWHAT doth not joy want! it is thirstier, heartier, hungrier, more frightful, more mysterious, than all woe: it wanteth ITSELF, it biteth into ITSELF, the ring‚Äôs will writheth in it,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîIt wanteth love, it wanteth hate, it is over-rich, it bestoweth, it throweth away, it beggeth for some one to take from it, it thanketh the taker, it would fain be hated,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîSo rich is joy that it thirsteth for woe, for hell, for hate, for shame, for the lame, for the WORLD,‚Äîfor this world, Oh, ye know it indeed!
U||Ye higher men, for you doth it long, this joy, this irrepressible, blessed joy‚Äîfor your woe, ye failures! For failures, longeth all eternal joy.
U||For joys all want themselves, therefore do they also want grief! O happiness, O pain! Oh break, thou heart! Ye higher men, do learn it, that joys want eternity.
U||‚ÄîJoys want the eternity of ALL things, they WANT DEEP, PROFOUND ETERNITY!
U||12.
U||Have ye now learned my song? Have ye divined what it would say? Well! Cheer up! Ye higher men, sing now my roundelay!
U||Sing now yourselves the song, the name of which is ‚ÄúOnce more,‚Äù the signification of which is ‚ÄúUnto all eternity!‚Äù‚Äîsing, ye higher men, Zarathustra‚Äôs roundelay!
U||     O man!  Take heed!
U||     What saith deep midnight‚Äôs voice indeed?
U||     ‚ÄúI slept my sleep‚Äî,
U||     ‚ÄúFrom deepest dream I‚Äôve woke, and plead:‚Äî
U||     ‚ÄúThe world is deep,
U||     ‚ÄúAnd deeper than the day could read.
U||     ‚ÄúDeep is its woe‚Äî,
U||     ‚ÄúJoy‚Äîdeeper still than grief can be:
U||     ‚ÄúWoe saith:  Hence!  Go!
U||     ‚ÄúBut joys all want eternity‚Äî,
U||     ‚Äú‚ÄîWant deep, profound eternity!‚Äù
U|| 
U||LXXX. THE SIGN.
U||In the morning, however, after this night, Zarathustra jumped up from his couch, and, having girded his loins, he came out of his cave glowing and strong, like a morning sun coming out of gloomy mountains.
U||‚ÄúThou great star,‚Äù spake he, as he had spoken once before, ‚Äúthou deep eye of happiness, what would be all thy happiness if thou hadst not THOSE for whom thou shinest!
U||And if they remained in their chambers whilst thou art already awake, and comest and bestowest and distributest, how would thy proud modesty upbraid for it!
U||Well! they still sleep, these higher men, whilst I am awake: THEY are not my proper companions! Not for them do I wait here in my mountains.
U||At my work I want to be, at my day: but they understand not what are the signs of my morning, my step‚Äîis not for them the awakening-call.
U||They still sleep in my cave; their dream still drinketh at my drunken songs. The audient ear for ME‚Äîthe OBEDIENT ear, is yet lacking in their limbs.‚Äù
U||‚ÄîThis had Zarathustra spoken to his heart when the sun arose: then looked he inquiringly aloft, for he heard above him the sharp call of his eagle. ‚ÄúWell!‚Äù called he upwards, ‚Äúthus is it pleasing and proper to me. Mine animals are awake, for I am awake.
U||Mine eagle is awake, and like me honoureth the sun. With eagle-talons doth it grasp at the new light. Ye are my proper animals; I love you.
U||But still do I lack my proper men!‚Äù‚Äî
U||Thus spake Zarathustra; then, however, it happened that all on a sudden he became aware that he was flocked around and fluttered around, as if by innumerable birds,‚Äîthe whizzing of so many wings, however, and the crowding around his head was so great that he shut his eyes. And verily, there came down upon him as it were a cloud, like a cloud of arrows which poureth upon a new enemy. But behold, here it was a cloud of love, and showered upon a new friend.
U||‚ÄúWhat happeneth unto me?‚Äù thought Zarathustra in his astonished heart, and slowly seated himself on the big stone which lay close to the exit from his cave. But while he grasped about with his hands, around him, above him and below him, and repelled the tender birds, behold, there then happened to him something still stranger: for he grasped thereby unawares into a mass of thick, warm, shaggy hair; at the same time, however, there sounded before him a roar,‚Äîa long, soft lion-roar.
U||‚ÄúTHE SIGN COMETH,‚Äù said Zarathustra, and a change came over his heart. And in truth, when it turned clear before him, there lay a yellow, powerful animal at his feet, resting its head on his knee,‚Äîunwilling to leave him out of love, and doing like a dog which again findeth its old master. The doves, however, were no less eager with their love than the lion; and whenever a dove whisked over its nose, the lion shook its head and wondered and laughed.
U||When all this went on Zarathustra spake only a word: ‚ÄúMY CHILDREN ARE NIGH, MY CHILDREN‚Äù‚Äî, then he became quite mute. His heart, however, was loosed, and from his eyes there dropped down tears and fell upon his hands. And he took no further notice of anything, but sat there motionless, without repelling the animals further. Then flew the doves to and fro, and perched on his shoulder, and caressed his white hair, and did not tire of their tenderness and joyousness. The strong lion, however, licked always the tears that fell on Zarathustra‚Äôs hands, and roared and growled shyly. Thus did these animals do.‚Äî
U||All this went on for a long time, or a short time: for properly speaking, there is NO time on earth for such things‚Äî. Meanwhile, however, the higher men had awakened in Zarathustra‚Äôs cave, and marshalled themselves for a procession to go to meet Zarathustra, and give him their morning greeting: for they had found when they awakened that he no longer tarried with them. When, however, they reached the door of the cave and the noise of their steps had preceded them, the lion started violently; it turned away all at once from Zarathustra, and roaring wildly, sprang towards the cave. The higher men, however, when they heard the lion roaring, cried all aloud as with one voice, fled back and vanished in an instant.
U||Zarathustra himself, however, stunned and strange, rose from his seat, looked around him, stood there astonished, inquired of his heart, bethought himself, and remained alone. ‚ÄúWhat did I hear?‚Äù said he at last, slowly, ‚Äúwhat happened unto me just now?‚Äù
U||But soon there came to him his recollection, and he took in at a glance all that had taken place between yesterday and to-day. ‚ÄúHere is indeed the stone,‚Äù said he, and stroked his beard, ‚Äúon IT sat I yester-morn; and here came the soothsayer unto me, and here heard I first the cry which I heard just now, the great cry of distress.
U||O ye higher men, YOUR distress was it that the old soothsayer foretold to me yester-morn,‚Äî
U||‚ÄîUnto your distress did he want to seduce and tempt me: ‚ÄòO Zarathustra,‚Äô said he to me, ‚ÄòI come to seduce thee to thy last sin.‚Äô
U||To my last sin?‚Äù cried Zarathustra, and laughed angrily at his own words: ‚ÄúWHAT hath been reserved for me as my last sin?‚Äù
U||‚ÄîAnd once more Zarathustra became absorbed in himself, and sat down again on the big stone and meditated. Suddenly he sprang up,‚Äî
U||‚ÄúFELLOW-SUFFERING! FELLOW-SUFFERING WITH THE HIGHER MEN!‚Äù he cried out, and his countenance changed into brass. ‚ÄúWell! THAT‚Äîhath had its time!
U||My suffering and my fellow-suffering‚Äîwhat matter about them! Do I then strive after HAPPINESS? I strive after my WORK!
U||Well! The lion hath come, my children are nigh, Zarathustra hath grown ripe, mine hour hath come:‚Äî
U||This is MY morning, MY day beginneth: ARISE NOW, ARISE, THOU GREAT NOONTIDE!‚Äù‚Äî
U||Thus spake Zarathustra and left his cave, glowing and strong, like a morning sun coming out of gloomy mountains.
U||APPENDIX.
U||NOTES ON ‚ÄúTHUS SPAKE ZARATHUSTRA‚Äù BY ANTHONY M. LUDOVICI.
U||I have had some opportunities of studying the conditions under which Nietzsche is read in Germany, France, and England, and I have found that, in each of these countries, students of his philosophy, as if actuated by precisely similar motives and desires, and misled by the same mistaken tactics on the part of most publishers, all proceed in the same happy-go-lucky style when ‚Äútaking him up.‚Äù They have had it said to them that he wrote without any system, and they very naturally conclude that it does not matter in the least whether they begin with his first, third, or last book, provided they can obtain a few vague ideas as to what his leading and most sensational principles were.
U||Now, it is clear that the book with the most mysterious, startling, or suggestive title, will always stand the best chance of being purchased by those who have no other criteria to guide them in their choice than the aspect of a title-page; and this explains why ‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù is almost always the first and often the only one of Nietzsche‚Äôs books that falls into the hands of the uninitiated.
U||The title suggests all kinds of mysteries; a glance at the chapter-headings quickly confirms the suspicions already aroused, and the sub-title: ‚ÄúA Book for All and None‚Äù, generally succeeds in dissipating the last doubts the prospective purchaser may entertain concerning his fitness for the book or its fitness for him. And what happens?
U||‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù is taken home; the reader, who perchance may know no more concerning Nietzsche than a magazine article has told him, tries to read it and, understanding less than half he reads, probably never gets further than the second or third part,‚Äîand then only to feel convinced that Nietzsche himself was ‚Äúrather hazy‚Äù as to what he was talking about. Such chapters as ‚ÄúThe Child with the Mirror‚Äù, ‚ÄúIn the Happy Isles‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Grave-Song,‚Äù ‚ÄúImmaculate Perception,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Stillest Hour‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Seven Seals‚Äù, and many others, are almost utterly devoid of meaning to all those who do not know something of Nietzsche‚Äôs life, his aims and his friendships.
U||As a matter of fact, ‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù, though it is unquestionably Nietzsche‚Äôs opus magnum, is by no means the first of Nietzsche‚Äôs works that the beginner ought to undertake to read. The author himself refers to it as the deepest work ever offered to the German public, and elsewhere speaks of his other writings as being necessary for the understanding of it. But when it is remembered that in Zarathustra we not only have the history of his most intimate experiences, friendships, feuds, disappointments, triumphs and the like, but that the very form in which they are narrated is one which tends rather to obscure than to throw light upon them, the difficulties which meet the reader who starts quite unprepared will be seen to be really formidable.
U||Zarathustra, then,‚Äîthis shadowy, allegorical personality, speaking in allegories and parables, and at times not even refraining from relating his own dreams‚Äîis a figure we can understand but very imperfectly if we have no knowledge of his creator and counterpart, Friedrich Nietzsche; and it were therefore well, previous to our study of the more abstruse parts of this book, if we were to turn to some authoritative book on Nietzsche‚Äôs life and works and to read all that is there said on the subject. Those who can read German will find an excellent guide, in this respect, in Frau Foerster-Nietzsche‚Äôs exhaustive and highly interesting biography of her brother: ‚ÄúDas Leben Friedrich Nietzsche‚Äôs‚Äù (published by Naumann); while the works of Deussen, Raoul Richter, and Baroness Isabelle von Unger-Sternberg, will be found to throw useful and necessary light upon many questions which it would be difficult for a sister to touch upon.
U||In regard to the actual philosophical views expounded in this work, there is an excellent way of clearing up any difficulties they may present, and that is by an appeal to Nietzsche‚Äôs other works. Again and again, of course, he will be found to express himself so clearly that all reference to his other writings may be dispensed with; but where this is not the case, the advice he himself gives is after all the best to be followed here, viz.:‚Äîto regard such works as: ‚ÄúJoyful Science‚Äù, ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Genealogy of Morals‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Twilight of the Idols‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Antichrist‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Will to Power‚Äù, etc., etc., as the necessary preparation for ‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù.
U||These directions, though they are by no means simple to carry out, seem at least to possess the quality of definiteness and straightforwardness. ‚ÄúFollow them and all will be clear,‚Äù I seem to imply. But I regret to say that this is not really the case. For my experience tells me that even after the above directions have been followed with the greatest possible zeal, the student will still halt in perplexity before certain passages in the book before us, and wonder what they mean. Now, it is with the view of giving a little additional help to all those who find themselves in this position that I proceed to put forth my own personal interpretation of the more abstruse passages in this work.
U||In offering this little commentary to the Nietzsche student, I should like it to be understood that I make no claim as to its infallibility or indispensability. It represents but an attempt on my part‚Äîa very feeble one perhaps‚Äîto give the reader what little help I can in surmounting difficulties which a long study of Nietzsche‚Äôs life and works has enabled me, partially I hope, to overcome.
U||...
U||Perhaps it would be as well to start out with a broad and rapid sketch of Nietzsche as a writer on Morals, Evolution, and Sociology, so that the reader may be prepared to pick out for himself, so to speak, all passages in this work bearing in any way upon Nietzsche‚Äôs views in those three important branches of knowledge.
U||(A.) Nietzsche and Morality.
U||In morality, Nietzsche starts out by adopting the position of the relativist. He says there are no absolute values ‚Äúgood‚Äù and ‚Äúevil‚Äù; these are mere means adopted by all in order to acquire power to maintain their place in the world, or to become supreme. It is the lion‚Äôs good to devour an antelope. It is the dead-leaf butterfly‚Äôs good to tell a foe a falsehood. For when the dead-leaf butterfly is in danger, it clings to the side of a twig, and what it says to its foe is practically this: ‚ÄúI am not a butterfly, I am a dead leaf, and can be of no use to thee.‚Äù This is a lie which is good to the butterfly, for it preserves it. In nature every species of organic being instinctively adopts and practises those acts which most conduce to the prevalence or supremacy of its kind. Once the most favourable order of conduct is found, proved efficient and established, it becomes the ruling morality of the species that adopts it and bears them along to victory. All species must not and cannot value alike,
U|| for what is the lion‚Äôs good is the antelope‚Äôs evil and vice versa.
U||Concepts of good and evil are therefore, in their origin, merely a means to an end, they are expedients for acquiring power.
U||Applying this principle to mankind, Nietzsche attacked Christian moral values. He declared them to be, like all other morals, merely an expedient for protecting a certain type of man. In the case of Christianity this type was, according to Nietzsche, a low one.
U||Conflicting moral codes have been no more than the conflicting weapons of different classes of men; for in mankind there is a continual war between the powerful, the noble, the strong, and the well-constituted on the one side, and the impotent, the mean, the weak, and the ill-constituted on the other. The war is a war of moral principles. The morality of the powerful class, Nietzsche calls NOBLE- or MASTER-MORALITY; that of the weak and subordinate class he calls SLAVE-MORALITY. In the first morality it is the eagle which, looking down upon a browsing lamb, contends that ‚Äúeating lamb is good.‚Äù In the second, the slave-morality, it is the lamb which, looking up from the sward, bleats dissentingly: ‚ÄúEating lamb is evil.‚Äù
U||(B.) The Master- and Slave-Morality Compared.
U||The first morality is active, creative, Dionysian. The second is passive, defensive,‚Äîto it belongs the ‚Äústruggle for existence.‚Äù
U||Where attempts have not been made to reconcile the two moralities, they may be described as follows:‚ÄîAll is GOOD in the noble morality which proceeds from strength, power, health, well-constitutedness, happiness, and awfulness; for, the motive force behind the people practising it is ‚Äúthe struggle for power.‚Äù The antithesis ‚Äúgood and bad‚Äù to this first class means the same as ‚Äúnoble‚Äù and ‚Äúdespicable.‚Äù ‚ÄúBad‚Äù in the master-morality must be applied to the coward, to all acts that spring from weakness, to the man with ‚Äúan eye to the main chance,‚Äù who would forsake everything in order to live.
U||With the second, the slave-morality, the case is different. There, inasmuch as the community is an oppressed, suffering, unemancipated, and weary one, all THAT will be held to be good which alleviates the state of suffering. Pity, the obliging hand, the warm heart, patience, industry, and humility‚Äîthese are unquestionably the qualities we shall here find flooded with the light of approval and admiration; because they are the most USEFUL qualities‚Äî; they make life endurable, they are of assistance in the ‚Äústruggle for existence‚Äù which is the motive force behind the people practising this morality. To this class, all that is AWFUL is bad, in fact it is THE evil par excellence. Strength, health, superabundance of animal spirits and power, are regarded with hate, suspicion, and fear by the subordinate class.
U||Now Nietzsche believed that the first or the noble-morality conduced to an ascent in the line of life; because it was creative and active. On the other hand, he believed that the second or slave-morality, where it became paramount, led to degeneration, because it was passive and defensive, wanting merely to keep those who practised it alive. Hence his earnest advocacy of noble-morality.
U||(C.) Nietzsche and Evolution.
U||Nietzsche as an evolutionist I shall have occasion to define and discuss in the course of these notes (see Notes on Chapter LVI., par.10, and on Chapter LVII.). For the present let it suffice for us to know that he accepted the ‚ÄúDevelopment Hypothesis‚Äù as an explanation of the origin of species: but he did not halt where most naturalists have halted. He by no means regarded man as the highest possible being which evolution could arrive at; for though his physical development may have reached its limit, this is not the case with his mental or spiritual attributes. If the process be a fact; if things have BECOME what they are, then, he contends, we may describe no limit to man‚Äôs aspirations. If he struggled up from barbarism, and still more remotely from the lower Primates, his ideal should be to surpass man himself and reach Superman (see especially the Prologue).
U||(D.) Nietzsche and Sociology.
U||Nietzsche as a sociologist aims at an aristocratic arrangement of society. He would have us rear an ideal race. Honest and truthful in intellectual matters, he could not even think that men are equal. ‚ÄúWith these preachers of equality will I not be mixed up and confounded. For thus speaketh justice unto ME: ‚ÄòMen are not equal.‚Äô‚Äù He sees precisely in this inequality a purpose to be served, a condition to be exploited. ‚ÄúEvery elevation of the type ‚Äòman,‚Äô‚Äù he writes in ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù, ‚Äúhas hitherto been the work of an aristocratic society‚Äîand so will it always be‚Äîa society believing in a long scale of gradations of rank and differences of worth among human beings.‚Äù
U||Those who are sufficiently interested to desire to read his own detailed account of the society he would fain establish, will find an excellent passage in Aphorism 57 of ‚ÄúThe Antichrist‚Äù.
U||...
U||PART I. THE PROLOGUE.
U||In Part I. including the Prologue, no very great difficulties will appear. Zarathustra‚Äôs habit of designating a whole class of men or a whole school of thought by a single fitting nickname may perhaps lead to a little confusion at first; but, as a rule, when the general drift of his arguments is grasped, it requires but a slight effort of the imagination to discover whom he is referring to. In the ninth paragraph of the Prologue, for instance, it is quite obvious that ‚ÄúHerdsmen‚Äù in the verse ‚ÄúHerdsmen, I say, etc., etc.,‚Äù stands for all those to-day who are the advocates of gregariousness‚Äîof the ant-hill. And when our author says: ‚ÄúA robber shall Zarathustra be called by the herdsmen,‚Äù it is clear that these words may be taken almost literally from one whose ideal was the rearing of a higher aristocracy. Again, ‚Äúthe good and just,‚Äù throughout the book, is the expression used in referring to the self-righteous of modern times,‚Äîthose who are quite sure that they know all that is to be kno
U||wn concerning good and evil, and are satisfied that the values their little world of tradition has handed down to them, are destined to rule mankind as long as it lasts.
U||In the last paragraph of the Prologue, verse 7, Zarathustra gives us a foretaste of his teaching concerning the big and the little sagacities, expounded subsequently. He says he would he were as wise as his serpent; this desire will be found explained in the discourse entitled ‚ÄúThe Despisers of the Body‚Äù, which I shall have occasion to refer to later.
U||... THE DISCOURSES.
U||Chapter I. The Three Metamorphoses.
U||This opening discourse is a parable in which Zarathustra discloses the mental development of all creators of new values. It is the story of a life which reaches its consummation in attaining to a second ingenuousness or in returning to childhood. Nietzsche, the supposed anarchist, here plainly disclaims all relationship whatever to anarchy, for he shows us that only by bearing the burdens of the existing law and submitting to it patiently, as the camel submits to being laden, does the free spirit acquire that ascendancy over tradition which enables him to meet and master the dragon ‚ÄúThou shalt,‚Äù‚Äîthe dragon with the values of a thousand years glittering on its scales. There are two lessons in this discourse: first, that in order to create one must be as a little child; secondly, that it is only through existing law and order that one attains to that height from which new law and new order may be promulgated.
U||Chapter II. The Academic Chairs of Virtue.
U||Almost the whole of this is quite comprehensible. It is a discourse against all those who confound virtue with tameness and smug ease, and who regard as virtuous only that which promotes security and tends to deepen sleep.
U||Chapter IV. The Despisers of the Body.
U||Here Zarathustra gives names to the intellect and the instincts; he calls the one ‚Äúthe little sagacity‚Äù and the latter ‚Äúthe big sagacity.‚Äù Schopenhauer‚Äôs teaching concerning the intellect is fully endorsed here. ‚ÄúAn instrument of thy body is also thy little sagacity, my brother, which thou callest ‚Äòspirit,‚Äô‚Äù says Zarathustra. From beginning to end it is a warning to those who would think too lightly of the instincts and unduly exalt the intellect and its derivatives: Reason and Understanding.
U||Chapter IX. The Preachers of Death.
U||This is an analysis of the psychology of all those who have the ‚Äúevil eye‚Äù and are pessimists by virtue of their constitutions.
U||Chapter XV. The Thousand and One Goals.
U||In this discourse Zarathustra opens his exposition of the doctrine of relativity in morality, and declares all morality to be a mere means to power. Needless to say that verses 9, 10, 11, and 12 refer to the Greeks, the Persians, the Jews, and the Germans respectively. In the penultimate verse he makes known his discovery concerning the root of modern Nihilism and indifference,‚Äîi.e., that modern man has no goal, no aim, no ideals (see Note A).
U||Chapter XVIII. Old and Young Women.
U||Nietzsche‚Äôs views on women have either to be loved at first sight or they become perhaps the greatest obstacle in the way of those who otherwise would be inclined to accept his philosophy. Women especially, of course, have been taught to dislike them, because it has been rumoured that his views are unfriendly to themselves. Now, to my mind, all this is pure misunderstanding and error.
U||German philosophers, thanks to Schopenhauer, have earned rather a bad name for their views on women. It is almost impossible for one of them to write a line on the subject, however kindly he may do so, without being suspected of wishing to open a crusade against the fair sex. Despite the fact, therefore, that all Nietzsche‚Äôs views in this respect were dictated to him by the profoundest love; despite Zarathustra‚Äôs reservation in this discourse, that ‚Äúwith women nothing (that can be said) is impossible,‚Äù and in the face of other overwhelming evidence to the contrary, Nietzsche is universally reported to have mis son pied dans le plat, where the female sex is concerned. And what is the fundamental doctrine which has given rise to so much bitterness and aversion?‚ÄîMerely this: that the sexes are at bottom ANTAGONISTIC‚Äîthat is to say, as different as blue is from yellow, and that the best possible means of rearing anything approaching a desirable race is to preserve and to foster this profound hostilit
U||y. What Nietzsche strives to combat and to overthrow is the modern democratic tendency which is slowly labouring to level all things‚Äîeven the sexes. His quarrel is not with women‚Äîwhat indeed could be more undignified?‚Äîit is with those who would destroy the natural relationship between the sexes, by modifying either the one or the other with a view to making them more alike. The human world is just as dependent upon women‚Äôs powers as upon men‚Äôs. It is women‚Äôs strongest and most valuable instincts which help to determine who are to be the fathers of the next generation. By destroying these particular instincts, that is to say by attempting to masculinise woman, and to feminise men, we jeopardise the future of our people. The general democratic movement of modern times, in its frantic struggle to mitigate all differences, is now invading even the world of sex. It is against this movement that Nietzsche raises his voice; he would have woman become ever more woman and man become ever more man. Only th
U||us, and he is undoubtedly right, can their combined instincts lead to the excellence of humanity. Regarded in this light, all his views on woman appear not only necessary but just (see Note on Chapter LVI., par. 21.)
U||It is interesting to observe that the last line of the discourse, which has so frequently been used by women as a weapon against Nietzsche‚Äôs views concerning them, was suggested to Nietzsche by a woman (see ‚ÄúDas Leben F. Nietzsche‚Äôs‚Äù).
U||Chapter XXI. Voluntary Death.
U||In regard to this discourse, I should only like to point out that Nietzsche had a particular aversion to the word ‚Äúsuicide‚Äù‚Äîself-murder. He disliked the evil it suggested, and in rechristening the act Voluntary Death, i.e., the death that comes from no other hand than one‚Äôs own, he was desirous of elevating it to the position it held in classical antiquity (see Aphorism 36 in ‚ÄúThe Twilight of the Idols‚Äù).
U||Chapter XXII. The Bestowing Virtue.
U||An important aspect of Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy is brought to light in this discourse. His teaching, as is well known, places the Aristotelian man of spirit, above all others in the natural divisions of man. The man with overflowing strength, both of mind and body, who must discharge this strength or perish, is the Nietzschean ideal. To such a man, giving from his overflow becomes a necessity; bestowing develops into a means of existence, and this is the only giving, the only charity, that Nietzsche recognises. In paragraph 3 of the discourse, we read Zarathustra‚Äôs healthy exhortation to his disciples to become independent thinkers and to find themselves before they learn any more from him (see Notes on Chapters LVI., par. 5, and LXXIII., pars. 10, 11).
U||...
U||PART II.
U||Chapter XXIII. The Child with the Mirror.
U||Nietzsche tells us here, in a poetical form, how deeply grieved he was by the manifold misinterpretations and misunderstandings which were becoming rife concerning his publications. He does not recognise himself in the mirror of public opinion, and recoils terrified from the distorted reflection of his features. In verse 20 he gives us a hint which it were well not to pass over too lightly; for, in the introduction to ‚ÄúThe Genealogy of Morals‚Äù (written in 1887) he finds it necessary to refer to the matter again and with greater precision. The point is this, that a creator of new values meets with his surest and strongest obstacles in the very spirit of the language which is at his disposal. Words, like all other manifestations of an evolving race, are stamped with the values that have long been paramount in that race. Now, the original thinker who finds himself compelled to use the current speech of his country in order to impart new and hitherto untried views to his fellows, imposes a task upon the natu
U||ral means of communication which it is totally unfitted to perform,‚Äîhence the obscurities and prolixities which are so frequently met with in the writings of original thinkers. In the ‚ÄúDawn of Day‚Äù, Nietzsche actually cautions young writers against THE DANGER OF ALLOWING THEIR THOUGHTS TO BE MOULDED BY THE WORDS AT THEIR DISPOSAL.
U||Chapter XXIV. In the Happy Isles.
U||While writing this, Nietzsche is supposed to have been thinking of the island of Ischia which was ultimately destroyed by an earthquake. His teaching here is quite clear. He was among the first thinkers of Europe to overcome the pessimism which godlessness generally brings in its wake. He points to creating as the surest salvation from the suffering which is a concomitant of all higher life. ‚ÄúWhat would there be to create,‚Äù he asks, ‚Äúif there were‚ÄîGods?‚Äù His ideal, the Superman, lends him the cheerfulness necessary to the overcoming of that despair usually attendant upon godlessness and upon the apparent aimlessness of a world without a god.
U||Chapter XXIX. The Tarantulas.
U||The tarantulas are the Socialists and Democrats. This discourse offers us an analysis of their mental attitude. Nietzsche refuses to be confounded with those resentful and revengeful ones who condemn society FROM BELOW, and whose criticism is only suppressed envy. ‚ÄúThere are those who preach my doctrine of life,‚Äù he says of the Nietzschean Socialists, ‚Äúand are at the same time preachers of equality and tarantulas‚Äù (see Notes on Chapter XL. and Chapter LI.).
U||Chapter XXX. The Famous Wise Ones.
U||This refers to all those philosophers hitherto, who have run in the harness of established values and have not risked their reputation with the people in pursuit of truth. The philosopher, however, as Nietzsche understood him, is a man who creates new values, and thus leads mankind in a new direction.
U||Chapter XXXIII. The Grave-Song.
U||Here Zarathustra sings about the ideals and friendships of his youth. Verses 27 to 31 undoubtedly refer to Richard Wagner (see Note on Chapter LXV.).
U||Chapter XXXIV. Self-Surpassing.
U||In this discourse we get the best exposition in the whole book of Nietzsche‚Äôs doctrine of the Will to Power. I go into this question thoroughly in the Note on Chapter LVII.
U||Nietzsche was not an iconoclast from choice. Those who hastily class him with the anarchists (or the Progressivists of the last century) fail to understand the high esteem in which he always held both law and discipline. In verse 41 of this most decisive discourse he truly explains his position when he says: ‚Äú...he who hath to be a creator in good and evil‚Äîverily he hath first to be a destroyer, and break values in pieces.‚Äù This teaching in regard to self-control is evidence enough of his reverence for law.
U||Chapter XXXV. The Sublime Ones.
U||These belong to a type which Nietzsche did not altogether dislike, but which he would fain have rendered more subtle and plastic. It is the type that takes life and itself too seriously, that never surmounts the camel-stage mentioned in the first discourse, and that is obdurately sublime and earnest. To be able to smile while speaking of lofty things and NOT TO BE OPPRESSED by them, is the secret of real greatness. He whose hand trembles when it lays hold of a beautiful thing, has the quality of reverence, without the artist‚Äôs unembarrassed friendship with the beautiful. Hence the mistakes which have arisen in regard to confounding Nietzsche with his extreme opposites the anarchists and agitators. For what they dare to touch and break with the impudence and irreverence of the unappreciative, he seems likewise to touch and break,‚Äîbut with other fingers‚Äîwith the fingers of the loving and unembarrassed artist who is on good terms with the beautiful and who feels able to create it and to enhance it with hi
U||s touch. The question of taste plays an important part in Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy, and verses 9, 10 of this discourse exactly state Nietzsche‚Äôs ultimate views on the subject. In the ‚ÄúSpirit of Gravity‚Äù, he actually cries:‚Äî‚ÄúNeither a good nor a bad taste, but MY taste, of which I have no longer either shame or secrecy.‚Äù
U||Chapter XXXVI. The Land of Culture.
U||This is a poetical epitome of some of the scathing criticism of scholars which appears in the first of the ‚ÄúThoughts out of Season‚Äù‚Äîthe polemical pamphlet (written in 1873) against David Strauss and his school. He reproaches his former colleagues with being sterile and shows them that their sterility is the result of their not believing in anything. ‚ÄúHe who had to create, had always his presaging dreams and astral premonitions‚Äîand believed in believing!‚Äù (See Note on Chapter LXXVII.) In the last two verses he reveals the nature of his altruism. How far it differs from that of Christianity we have already read in the discourse ‚ÄúNeighbour-Love‚Äù, but here he tells us definitely the nature of his love to mankind; he explains why he was compelled to assail the Christian values of pity and excessive love of the neighbour, not only because they are slave-values and therefore tend to promote degeneration (see Note B.), but because he could only love his children‚Äôs land, the undiscovered land in a r
U||emote sea; because he would fain retrieve the errors of his fathers in his children.
U||Chapter XXXVII. Immaculate Perception.
U||An important feature of Nietzsche‚Äôs interpretation of Life is disclosed in this discourse. As Buckle suggests in his ‚ÄúInfluence of Women on the Progress of Knowledge‚Äù, the scientific spirit of the investigator is both helped and supplemented by the latter‚Äôs emotions and personality, and the divorce of all emotionalism and individual temperament from science is a fatal step towards sterility. Zarathustra abjures all those who would fain turn an IMPERSONAL eye upon nature and contemplate her phenomena with that pure objectivity to which the scientific idealists of to-day would so much like to attain. He accuses such idealists of hypocrisy and guile; he says they lack innocence in their desires and therefore slander all desiring.
U||Chapter XXXVIII. Scholars.
U||This is a record of Nietzsche‚Äôs final breach with his former colleagues‚Äîthe scholars of Germany. Already after the publication of the ‚ÄúBirth of Tragedy‚Äù, numbers of German philologists and professional philosophers had denounced him as one who had strayed too far from their flock, and his lectures at the University of Bale were deserted in consequence; but it was not until 1879, when he finally severed all connection with University work, that he may be said to have attained to the freedom and independence which stamp this discourse.
U||Chapter XXXIX. Poets.
U||People have sometimes said that Nietzsche had no sense of humour. I have no intention of defending him here against such foolish critics; I should only like to point out to the reader that we have him here at his best, poking fun at himself, and at his fellow-poets (see Note on Chapter LXIII., pars. 16, 17, 18, 19, 20).
U||Chapter XL. Great Events.
U||Here we seem to have a puzzle. Zarathustra himself, while relating his experience with the fire-dog to his disciples, fails to get them interested in his narrative, and we also may be only too ready to turn over these pages under the impression that they are little more than a mere phantasy or poetical flight. Zarathustra‚Äôs interview with the fire-dog is, however, of great importance. In it we find Nietzsche face to face with the creature he most sincerely loathes‚Äîthe spirit of revolution, and we obtain fresh hints concerning his hatred of the anarchist and rebel. ‚Äú‚ÄòFreedom‚Äô ye all roar most eagerly,‚Äù he says to the fire-dog, ‚Äúbut I have unlearned the belief in ‚ÄòGreat Events‚Äô when there is much roaring and smoke about them. Not around the inventors of new noise, but around the inventors of new values, doth the world revolve; INAUDIBLY it revolveth.‚Äù
U||Chapter XLI. The Soothsayer.
U||This refers, of course, to Schopenhauer. Nietzsche, as is well known, was at one time an ardent follower of Schopenhauer. He overcame Pessimism by discovering an object in existence; he saw the possibility of raising society to a higher level and preached the profoundest Optimism in consequence.
U||Chapter XLII. Redemption.
U||Zarathustra here addresses cripples. He tells them of other cripples‚Äîthe GREAT MEN in this world who have one organ or faculty inordinately developed at the cost of their other faculties. This is doubtless a reference to a fact which is too often noticeable in the case of so many of the world‚Äôs giants in art, science, or religion. In verse 19 we are told what Nietzsche called Redemption‚Äîthat is to say, the ability to say of all that is past: ‚ÄúThus would I have it.‚Äù The in ability to say this, and the resentment which results therefrom, he regards as the source of all our feelings of revenge, and all our desires to punish‚Äîpunishment meaning to him merely a euphemism for the word revenge, invented in order to still our consciences. He who can be proud of his enemies, who can be grateful to them for the obstacles they have put in his way; he who can regard his worst calamity as but the extra strain on the bow of his life, which is to send the arrow of his longing even further than he could have hope
U||d;‚Äîthis man knows no revenge, neither does he know despair, he truly has found redemption and can turn on the worst in his life and even in himself, and call it his best (see Notes on Chapter LVII.).
U||Chapter XLIII. Manly Prudence.
U||This discourse is very important. In ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù we hear often enough that the select and superior man must wear a mask, and here we find this injunction explained. ‚ÄúAnd he who would not languish amongst men, must learn to drink out of all glasses: and he who would keep clean amongst men, must know how to wash himself even with dirty water.‚Äù This, I venture to suggest, requires some explanation. At a time when individuality is supposed to be shown most tellingly by putting boots on one‚Äôs hands and gloves on one‚Äôs feet, it is somewhat refreshing to come across a true individualist who feels the chasm between himself and others so deeply, that he must perforce adapt himself to them outwardly, at least, in all respects, so that the inner difference should be overlooked. Nietzsche practically tells us here that it is not he who intentionally wears eccentric clothes or does eccentric things who is truly the individualist. The profound man, who is by nature differentiated from his fellows, f
U||eels this difference too keenly to call attention to it by any outward show. He is shamefast and bashful with those who surround him and wishes not to be discovered by them, just as one instinctively avoids all lavish display of comfort or wealth in the presence of a poor friend.
U||Chapter XLIV. The Stillest Hour.
U||This seems to me to give an account of the great struggle which must have taken place in Nietzsche‚Äôs soul before he finally resolved to make known the more esoteric portions of his teaching. Our deepest feelings crave silence. There is a certain self-respect in the serious man which makes him hold his profoundest feelings sacred. Before they are uttered they are full of the modesty of a virgin, and often the oldest sage will blush like a girl when this virginity is violated by an indiscretion which forces him to reveal his deepest thoughts.
U||...
U||PART III.
U||This is perhaps the most important of all the four parts. If it contained only ‚ÄúThe Vision and the Enigma‚Äù and ‚ÄúThe Old and New Tables‚Äù I should still be of this opinion; for in the former of these discourses we meet with what Nietzsche regarded as the crowning doctrine of his philosophy and in ‚ÄúThe Old and New Tables‚Äù we have a valuable epitome of practically all his leading principles.
U||Chapter XLVI. The Vision and the Enigma.
U||‚ÄúThe Vision and the Enigma‚Äù is perhaps an example of Nietzsche in his most obscure vein. We must know how persistently he inveighed against the oppressing and depressing influence of man‚Äôs sense of guilt and consciousness of sin in order fully to grasp the significance of this discourse. Slowly but surely, he thought the values of Christianity and Judaic traditions had done their work in the minds of men. What were once but expedients devised for the discipline of a certain portion of humanity, had now passed into man‚Äôs blood and had become instincts. This oppressive and paralysing sense of guilt and of sin is what Nietzsche refers to when he speaks of ‚Äúthe spirit of gravity.‚Äù This creature half-dwarf, half-mole, whom he bears with him a certain distance on his climb and finally defies, and whom he calls his devil and arch-enemy, is nothing more than the heavy millstone ‚Äúguilty conscience,‚Äù together with the concept of sin which at present hangs round the neck of men. To rise above it‚Äîto so
U||ar‚Äîis the most difficult of all things to-day. Nietzsche is able to think cheerfully and optimistically of the possibility of life in this world recurring again and again, when he has once cast the dwarf from his shoulders, and he announces his doctrine of the Eternal Recurrence of all things great and small to his arch-enemy and in defiance of him.
U||That there is much to be said for Nietzsche‚Äôs hypothesis of the Eternal Recurrence of all things great and small, nobody who has read the literature on the subject will doubt for an instant; but it remains a very daring conjecture notwithstanding and even in its ultimate effect, as a dogma, on the minds of men, I venture to doubt whether Nietzsche ever properly estimated its worth (see Note on Chapter LVII.).
U||What follows is clear enough. Zarathustra sees a young shepherd struggling on the ground with a snake holding fast to the back of his throat. The sage, assuming that the snake must have crawled into the young man‚Äôs mouth while he lay sleeping, runs to his help and pulls at the loathsome reptile with all his might, but in vain. At last, in despair, Zarathustra appeals to the young man‚Äôs will. Knowing full well what a ghastly operation he is recommending, he nevertheless cries, ‚ÄúBite! Bite! Its head off! Bite!‚Äù as the only possible solution of the difficulty. The young shepherd bites, and far away he spits the snake‚Äôs head, whereupon he rises, ‚ÄúNo longer shepherd, no longer man‚Äîa transfigured being, a light-surrounded being, that LAUGHED! Never on earth laughed a man as he laughed!‚Äù
U||In this parable the young shepherd is obviously the man of to-day; the snake that chokes him represents the stultifying and paralysing social values that threaten to shatter humanity, and the advice ‚ÄúBite! Bite!‚Äù is but Nietzsche‚Äôs exasperated cry to mankind to alter their values before it is too late.
U||Chapter XLVII. Involuntary Bliss.
U||This, like ‚ÄúThe Wanderer‚Äù, is one of the many introspective passages in the work, and is full of innuendos and hints as to the Nietzschean outlook on life.
U||Chapter XLVIII. Before Sunrise.
U||Here we have a record of Zarathustra‚Äôs avowal of optimism, as also the important statement concerning ‚ÄúChance‚Äù or ‚ÄúAccident‚Äù (verse 27). Those who are familiar with Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy will not require to be told what an important role his doctrine of chance plays in his teaching. The Giant Chance has hitherto played with the puppet ‚Äúman,‚Äù‚Äîthis is the fact he cannot contemplate with equanimity. Man shall now exploit chance, he says again and again, and make it fall on its knees before him! (See verse 33 in ‚ÄúOn the Olive-Mount‚Äù, and verses 9-10 in ‚ÄúThe Bedwarfing Virtue‚Äù).
U||Chapter XLIX. The Bedwarfing Virtue.
U||This requires scarcely any comment. It is a satire on modern man and his belittling virtues. In verses 23 and 24 of the second part of the discourse we are reminded of Nietzsche‚Äôs powerful indictment of the great of to-day, in the Antichrist (Aphorism 43):‚Äî‚ÄúAt present nobody has any longer the courage for separate rights, for rights of domination, for a feeling of reverence for himself and his equals,‚ÄîFOR PATHOS OF DISTANCE.... Our politics are MORBID from this want of courage!‚ÄîThe aristocracy of character has been undermined most craftily by the lie of the equality of souls; and if the belief in the ‚Äòprivilege of the many,‚Äô makes revolutions and WILL CONTINUE TO MAKE them, it is Christianity, let us not doubt it, it is CHRISTIAN valuations, which translate every revolution merely into blood and crime!‚Äù (see also ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù, pages 120, 121). Nietzsche thought it was a bad sign of the times that even rulers have lost the courage of their positions, and that a man of Frederick t
U||he Great‚Äôs power and distinguished gifts should have been able to say: ‚ÄúIch bin der erste Diener des Staates‚Äù (I am the first servant of the State.) To this utterance of the great sovereign, verse 24 undoubtedly refers. ‚ÄúCowardice‚Äù and ‚ÄúMediocrity,‚Äù are the names with which he labels modern notions of virtue and moderation.
U||In Part III., we get the sentiments of the discourse ‚ÄúIn the Happy Isles‚Äù, but perhaps in stronger terms. Once again we find Nietzsche thoroughly at ease, if not cheerful, as an atheist, and speaking with vertiginous daring of making chance go on its knees to him. In verse 20, Zarathustra makes yet another attempt at defining his entirely anti-anarchical attitude, and unless such passages have been completely overlooked or deliberately ignored hitherto by those who will persist in laying anarchy at his door, it is impossible to understand how he ever became associated with that foul political party.
U||The last verse introduces the expression, ‚ÄúTHE GREAT NOONTIDE!‚Äù In the poem to be found at the end of ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù, we meet with the expression again, and we shall find it occurring time and again in Nietzsche‚Äôs works. It will be found fully elucidated in the fifth part of ‚ÄúThe Twilight of the Idols‚Äù; but for those who cannot refer to this book, it were well to point out that Nietzsche called the present period‚Äîour period‚Äîthe noon of man‚Äôs history. Dawn is behind us. The childhood of mankind is over. Now we KNOW; there is now no longer any excuse for mistakes which will tend to botch and disfigure the type man. ‚ÄúWith respect to what is past,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have, like all discerning ones, great toleration, that is to say, GENEROUS self-control.... But my feeling changes suddenly, and breaks out as soon as I enter the modern period, OUR period. Our age KNOWS...‚Äù (See Note on Chapter LXX.).
U||Chapter LI. On Passing-by.
U||Here we find Nietzsche confronted with his extreme opposite, with him therefore for whom he is most frequently mistaken by the unwary. ‚ÄúZarathustra‚Äôs ape‚Äù he is called in the discourse. He is one of those at whose hands Nietzsche had to suffer most during his life-time, and at whose hands his philosophy has suffered most since his death. In this respect it may seem a little trivial to speak of extremes meeting; but it is wonderfully apt. Many have adopted Nietzsche‚Äôs mannerisms and word-coinages, who had nothing in common with him beyond the ideas and ‚Äúbusiness‚Äù they plagiarised; but the superficial observer and a large portion of the public, not knowing of these things,‚Äînot knowing perhaps that there are iconoclasts who destroy out of love and are therefore creators, and that there are others who destroy out of resentment and revengefulness and who are therefore revolutionists and anarchists,‚Äîare prone to confound the two, to the detriment of the nobler type.
U||If we now read what the fool says to Zarathustra, and note the tricks of speech he has borrowed from him: if we carefully follow the attitude he assumes, we shall understand why Zarathustra finally interrupts him. ‚ÄúStop this at once,‚Äù Zarathustra cries, ‚Äúlong have thy speech and thy species disgusted me.... Out of love alone shall my contempt and my warning bird take wing; BUT NOT OUT OF THE SWAMP!‚Äù It were well if this discourse were taken to heart by all those who are too ready to associate Nietzsche with lesser and noiser men,‚Äîwith mountebanks and mummers.
U||Chapter LII. The Apostates.
U||It is clear that this applies to all those breathless and hasty ‚Äútasters of everything,‚Äù who plunge too rashly into the sea of independent thought and ‚Äúheresy,‚Äù and who, having miscalculated their strength, find it impossible to keep their head above water. ‚ÄúA little older, a little colder,‚Äù says Nietzsche. They soon clamber back to the conventions of the age they intended reforming. The French then say ‚Äúle diable se fait hermite,‚Äù but these men, as a rule, have never been devils, neither do they become angels; for, in order to be really good or evil, some strength and deep breathing is required. Those who are more interested in supporting orthodoxy than in being over nice concerning the kind of support they give it, often refer to these people as evidence in favour of the true faith.
U||Chapter LIII. The Return Home.
U||This is an example of a class of writing which may be passed over too lightly by those whom poetasters have made distrustful of poetry. From first to last it is extremely valuable as an autobiographical note. The inevitable superficiality of the rabble is contrasted with the peaceful and profound depths of the anchorite. Here we first get a direct hint concerning Nietzsche‚Äôs fundamental passion‚Äîthe main force behind all his new values and scathing criticism of existing values. In verse 30 we are told that pity was his greatest danger. The broad altruism of the law-giver, thinking over vast eras of time, was continually being pitted by Nietzsche, in himself, against that transient and meaner sympathy for the neighbour which he more perhaps than any of his contemporaries had suffered from, but which he was certain involved enormous dangers not only for himself but also to the next and subsequent generations (see Note B., where ‚Äúpity‚Äù is mentioned among the degenerate virtues). Later in the book we shal
U||l see how his profound compassion leads him into temptation, and how frantically he struggles against it. In verses 31 and 32, he tells us to what extent he had to modify himself in order to be endured by his fellows whom he loved (see also verse 12 in ‚ÄúManly Prudence‚Äù). Nietzsche‚Äôs great love for his fellows, which he confesses in the Prologue, and which is at the root of all his teaching, seems rather to elude the discerning powers of the average philanthropist and modern man. He cannot see the wood for the trees. A philanthropy that sacrifices the minority of the present-day for the majority constituting posterity, completely evades his mental grasp, and Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy, because it declares Christian values to be a danger to the future of our kind, is therefore shelved as brutal, cold, and hard (see Note on Chapter XXXVI.). Nietzsche tried to be all things to all men; he was sufficiently fond of his fellows for that: in the Return Home he describes how he ultimately returns to loneliness in
U|| order to recover from the effects of his experiment.
U||Chapter LIV. The Three Evil Things.
U||Nietzsche is here completely in his element. Three things hitherto best cursed and most calumniated on earth, are brought forward to be weighed. Voluptuousness, thirst of power, and selfishness,‚Äîthe three forces in humanity which Christianity has done most to garble and besmirch,‚ÄîNietzsche endeavours to reinstate in their former places of honour. Voluptuousness, or sensual pleasure, is a dangerous thing to discuss nowadays. If we mention it with favour we may be regarded, however unjustly, as the advocate of savages, satyrs, and pure sensuality. If we condemn it, we either go over to the Puritans or we join those who are wont to come to table with no edge to their appetites and who therefore grumble at all good fare. There can be no doubt that the value of healthy innocent voluptuousness, like the value of health itself, must have been greatly discounted by all those who, resenting their inability to partake of this world‚Äôs goods, cried like St Paul: ‚ÄúI would that all men were even as I myself.‚Äù No
U||w Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy might be called an attempt at giving back to healthy and normal men innocence and a clean conscience in their desires‚ÄîNOT to applaud the vulgar sensualists who respond to every stimulus and whose passions are out of hand; not to tell the mean, selfish individual, whose selfishness is a pollution (see Aphorism 33, ‚ÄúTwilight of the Idols‚Äù), that he is right, nor to assure the weak, the sick, and the crippled, that the thirst of power, which they gratify by exploiting the happier and healthier individuals, is justified;‚Äîbut to save the clean healthy man from the values of those around him, who look at everything through the mud that is in their own bodies,‚Äîto give him, and him alone, a clean conscience in his manhood and the desires of his manhood. ‚ÄúDo I counsel you to slay your instincts? I counsel to innocence in your instincts.‚Äù In verse 7 of the second paragraph (as in verse I of paragraph 19 in ‚ÄúThe Old and New Tables‚Äù) Nietzsche gives us a reason for his occasi
U||onal obscurity (see also verses 3 to 7 of ‚ÄúPoets‚Äù). As I have already pointed out, his philosophy is quite esoteric. It can serve no purpose with the ordinary, mediocre type of man. I, personally, can no longer have any doubt that Nietzsche‚Äôs only object, in that part of his philosophy where he bids his friends stand ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù with him, was to save higher men, whose growth and scope might be limited by the too strict observance of modern values from foundering on the rocks of a ‚ÄúCompromise‚Äù between their own genius and traditional conventions. The only possible way in which the great man can achieve greatness is by means of exceptional freedom‚Äîthe freedom which assists him in experiencing HIMSELF. Verses 20 to 30 afford an excellent supplement to Nietzsche‚Äôs description of the attitude of the noble type towards the slaves in Aphorism 260 of the work ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù (see also Note B.)
U||Chapter LV. The Spirit of Gravity.
U||(See Note on Chapter XLVI.) In Part II. of this discourse we meet with a doctrine not touched upon hitherto, save indirectly;‚ÄîI refer to the doctrine of self-love. We should try to understand this perfectly before proceeding; for it is precisely views of this sort which, after having been cut out of the original context, are repeated far and wide as internal evidence proving the general unsoundness of Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy. Already in the last of the ‚ÄúThoughts out of Season‚Äù Nietzsche speaks as follows about modern men: ‚Äú...these modern creatures wish rather to be hunted down, wounded and torn to shreds, than to live alone with themselves in solitary calm. Alone with oneself!‚Äîthis thought terrifies the modern soul; it is his one anxiety, his one ghastly fear‚Äù (English Edition, page 141). In his feverish scurry to find entertainment and diversion, whether in a novel, a newspaper, or a play, the modern man condemns his own age utterly; for he shows that in his heart of hearts he despises himself
U||. One cannot change a condition of this sort in a day; to become endurable to oneself an inner transformation is necessary. Too long have we lost ourselves in our friends and entertainments to be able to find ourselves so soon at another‚Äôs bidding. ‚ÄúAnd verily, it is no commandment for to-day and to-morrow to LEARN to love oneself. Rather is it of all arts the finest, subtlest, last, and patientest.‚Äù
U||In the last verse Nietzsche challenges us to show that our way is the right way. In his teaching he does not coerce us, nor does he overpersuade; he simply says: ‚ÄúI am a law only for mine own, I am not a law for all. This‚Äîis now MY way,‚Äîwhere is yours?‚Äù
U||Chapter LVI. Old and New Tables. Par. 2.
U||Nietzsche himself declares this to be the most decisive portion of the whole of ‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù. It is a sort of epitome of his leading doctrines. In verse 12 of the second paragraph, we learn how he himself would fain have abandoned the poetical method of expression had he not known only too well that the only chance a new doctrine has of surviving, nowadays, depends upon its being given to the world in some kind of art-form. Just as prophets, centuries ago, often had to have recourse to the mask of madness in order to mitigate the hatred of those who did not and could not see as they did; so, to-day, the struggle for existence among opinions and values is so great, that an art-form is practically the only garb in which a new philosophy can dare to introduce itself to us.
U||Pars. 3 and 4.
U||Many of the paragraphs will be found to be merely reminiscent of former discourses. For instance, par. 3 recalls ‚ÄúRedemption‚Äù. The last verse of par. 4 is important. Freedom which, as I have pointed out before, Nietzsche considered a dangerous acquisition in inexperienced or unworthy hands, here receives its death-blow as a general desideratum. In the first Part we read under ‚ÄúThe Way of the Creating One‚Äù, that freedom as an end in itself does not concern Zarathustra at all. He says there: ‚ÄúFree from what? What doth that matter to Zarathustra? Clearly, however, shall thine eye answer me: free FOR WHAT?‚Äù And in ‚ÄúThe Bedwarfing Virtue‚Äù: ‚ÄúAh that ye understood my word: ‚ÄòDo ever what ye will‚Äîbut first be such as CAN WILL.‚Äô‚Äù
U||Par. 5.
U||Here we have a description of the kind of altruism Nietzsche exacted from higher men. It is really a comment upon ‚ÄúThe Bestowing Virtue‚Äù (see Note on Chapter XXII.).
U||Par. 6.
U||This refers, of course, to the reception pioneers of Nietzsche‚Äôs stamp meet with at the hands of their contemporaries.
U||Par. 8.
U||Nietzsche teaches that nothing is stable,‚Äînot even values,‚Äînot even the concepts good and evil. He likens life unto a stream. But foot-bridges and railings span the stream, and they seem to stand firm. Many will be reminded of good and evil when they look upon these structures; for thus these same values stand over the stream of life, and life flows on beneath them and leaves them standing. When, however, winter comes and the stream gets frozen, many inquire: ‚ÄúShould not everything‚ÄîSTAND STILL? Fundamentally everything standeth still.‚Äù But soon the spring cometh and with it the thaw-wind. It breaks the ice, and the ice breaks down the foot-bridges and railings, whereupon everything is swept away. This state of affairs, according to Nietzsche, has now been reached. ‚ÄúOh, my brethren, is not everything AT PRESENT IN FLUX? Have not all railings and foot-bridges fallen into the water? Who would still HOLD ON to ‚Äògood‚Äô and ‚Äòevil‚Äô?‚Äù
U||Par. 9.
U||This is complementary to the first three verses of par. 2.
U||Par. 10.
U||So far, this is perhaps the most important paragraph. It is a protest against reading a moral order of things in life. ‚ÄúLife is something essentially immoral!‚Äù Nietzsche tells us in the introduction to the ‚ÄúBirth of Tragedy‚Äù. Even to call life ‚Äúactivity,‚Äù or to define it further as ‚Äúthe continuous adjustment of internal relations to external relations,‚Äù as Spencer has it, Nietzsche characterises as a ‚Äúdemocratic idiosyncracy.‚Äù He says to define it in this way, ‚Äúis to mistake the true nature and function of life, which is Will to Power.... Life is ESSENTIALLY appropriation, injury, conquest of the strange and weak, suppression, severity, obtrusion of its own forms, incorporation and at least, putting it mildest, exploitation.‚Äù Adaptation is merely a secondary activity, a mere re-activity (see Note on Chapter LVII.).
U||Pars. 11, 12.
U||These deal with Nietzsche‚Äôs principle of the desirability of rearing a select race. The biological and historical grounds for his insistence upon this principle are, of course, manifold. Gobineau in his great work, ‚ÄúL‚ÄôInegalite des Races Humaines‚Äù, lays strong emphasis upon the evils which arise from promiscuous and inter-social marriages. He alone would suffice to carry Nietzsche‚Äôs point against all those who are opposed to the other conditions, to the conditions which would have saved Rome, which have maintained the strength of the Jewish race, and which are strictly maintained by every breeder of animals throughout the world. Darwin in his remarks relative to the degeneration of CULTIVATED types of animals through the action of promiscuous breeding, brings Gobineau support from the realm of biology.
U||The last two verses of par. 12 were discussed in the Notes on Chapters XXXVI. and LIII.
U||Par. 13.
U||This, like the first part of ‚ÄúThe Soothsayer‚Äù, is obviously a reference to the Schopenhauerian Pessimism.
U||Pars. 14, 15, 16, 17.
U||These are supplementary to the discourse ‚ÄúBackworld‚Äôs-men‚Äù.
U||Par. 18.
U||We must be careful to separate this paragraph, in sense, from the previous four paragraphs. Nietzsche is still dealing with Pessimism here; but it is the pessimism of the hero‚Äîthe man most susceptible of all to desperate views of life, owing to the obstacles that are arrayed against him in a world where men of his kind are very rare and are continually being sacrificed. It was to save this man that Nietzsche wrote. Heroism foiled, thwarted, and wrecked, hoping and fighting until the last, is at length overtaken by despair, and renounces all struggle for sleep. This is not the natural or constitutional pessimism which proceeds from an unhealthy body‚Äîthe dyspeptic‚Äôs lack of appetite; it is rather the desperation of the netted lion that ultimately stops all movement, because the more it moves the more involved it becomes.
U||Par. 20.
U||‚ÄúAll that increases power is good, all that springs from weakness is bad. The weak and ill-constituted shall perish: first principle of our charity. And one shall also help them thereto.‚Äù Nietzsche partly divined the kind of reception moral values of this stamp would meet with at the hands of the effeminate manhood of Europe. Here we see that he had anticipated the most likely form their criticism would take (see also the last two verses of par. 17).
U||Par. 21.
U||The first ten verses, here, are reminiscent of ‚ÄúWar and Warriors‚Äù and of ‚ÄúThe Flies in the Market-place.‚Äù Verses 11 and 12, however, are particularly important. There is a strong argument in favour of the sharp differentiation of castes and of races (and even of sexes; see Note on Chapter XVIII.) running all through Nietzsche‚Äôs writings. But sharp differentiation also implies antagonism in some form or other‚Äîhence Nietzsche‚Äôs fears for modern men. What modern men desire above all, is peace and the cessation of pain. But neither great races nor great castes have ever been built up in this way. ‚ÄúWho still wanteth to rule?‚Äù Zarathustra asks in the ‚ÄúPrologue‚Äù. ‚ÄúWho still wanteth to obey? Both are too burdensome.‚Äù This is rapidly becoming everybody‚Äôs attitude to-day. The tame moral reading of the face of nature, together with such democratic interpretations of life as those suggested by Herbert Spencer, are signs of a physiological condition which is the reverse of that bounding and ir
U||responsible healthiness in which harder and more tragic values rule.
U||Par. 24.
U||This should be read in conjunction with ‚ÄúChild and Marriage‚Äù. In the fifth verse we shall recognise our old friend ‚ÄúMarriage on the ten-years system,‚Äù which George Meredith suggested some years ago. This, however, must not be taken too literally. I do not think Nietzsche‚Äôs profoundest views on marriage were ever intended to be given over to the public at all, at least not for the present. They appear in the biography by his sister, and although their wisdom is unquestionable, the nature of the reforms he suggests render it impossible for them to become popular just now.
U||Pars. 26, 27.
U||See Note on ‚ÄúThe Prologue‚Äù.
U||Par. 28.
U||Nietzsche was not an iconoclast from predilection. No bitterness or empty hate dictated his vituperations against existing values and against the dogmas of his parents and forefathers. He knew too well what these things meant to the millions who profess them, to approach the task of uprooting them with levity or even with haste. He saw what modern anarchists and revolutionists do NOT see‚Äînamely, that man is in danger of actual destruction when his customs and values are broken. I need hardly point out, therefore, how deeply he was conscious of the responsibility he threw upon our shoulders when he invited us to reconsider our position. The lines in this paragraph are evidence enough of his earnestness.
U||Chapter LVII. The Convalescent.
U||We meet with several puzzles here. Zarathustra calls himself the advocate of the circle (the Eternal Recurrence of all things), and he calls this doctrine his abysmal thought. In the last verse of the first paragraph, however, after hailing his deepest thought, he cries: ‚ÄúDisgust, disgust, disgust!‚Äù We know Nietzsche‚Äôs ideal man was that ‚Äúworld-approving, exuberant, and vivacious creature, who has not only learnt to compromise and arrange with that which was and is, but wishes to have it again, AS IT WAS AND IS, for all eternity insatiably calling out da capo, not only to himself, but to the whole piece and play‚Äù (see Note on Chapter XLII.). But if one ask oneself what the conditions to such an attitude are, one will realise immediately how utterly different Nietzsche was from his ideal. The man who insatiably cries da capo to himself and to the whole of his mise-en-scene, must be in a position to desire every incident in his life to be repeated, not once, but again and again eternally. Now, Nietzs
U||che‚Äôs life had been too full of disappointments, illness, unsuccessful struggles, and snubs, to allow of his thinking of the Eternal Recurrence without loathing‚Äîhence probably the words of the last verse.
U||In verses 15 and 16, we have Nietzsche declaring himself an evolutionist in the broadest sense‚Äîthat is to say, that he believes in the Development Hypothesis as the description of the process by which species have originated. Now, to understand his position correctly we must show his relationship to the two greatest of modern evolutionists‚ÄîDarwin and Spencer. As a philosopher, however, Nietzsche does not stand or fall by his objections to the Darwinian or Spencerian cosmogony. He never laid claim to a very profound knowledge of biology, and his criticism is far more valuable as the attitude of a fresh mind than as that of a specialist towards the question. Moreover, in his objections many difficulties are raised which are not settled by an appeal to either of the men above mentioned. We have given Nietzsche‚Äôs definition of life in the Note on Chapter LVI., par. 10. Still, there remains a hope that Darwin and Nietzsche may some day become reconciled by a new description of the processes by which varieti
U||es occur. The appearance of varieties among animals and of ‚Äúsporting plants‚Äù in the vegetable kingdom, is still shrouded in mystery, and the question whether this is not precisely the ground on which Darwin and Nietzsche will meet, is an interesting one. The former says in his ‚ÄúOrigin of Species‚Äù, concerning the causes of variability: ‚Äú...there are two factors, namely, the nature of the organism, and the nature of the conditions. THE FORMER SEEMS TO BE MUCH THE MORE IMPORTANT (The italics are mine.), for nearly similar variations sometimes arise under, as far as we can judge, dissimilar conditions; and on the other hand, dissimilar variations arise under conditions which appear to be nearly uniform.‚Äù Nietzsche, recognising this same truth, would ascribe practically all the importance to the ‚Äúhighest functionaries in the organism, in which the life-will appears as an active and formative principle,‚Äù and except in certain cases (where passive organisms alone are concerned) would not give such a
U|| prominent place to the influence of environment. Adaptation, according to him, is merely a secondary activity, a mere re-activity, and he is therefore quite opposed to Spencer‚Äôs definition: ‚ÄúLife is the continuous adjustment of internal relations to external relations.‚Äù Again in the motive force behind animal and plant life, Nietzsche disagrees with Darwin. He transforms the ‚ÄúStruggle for Existence‚Äù‚Äîthe passive and involuntary condition‚Äîinto the ‚ÄúStruggle for Power,‚Äù which is active and creative, and much more in harmony with Darwin‚Äôs own view, given above, concerning the importance of the organism itself. The change is one of such far-reaching importance that we cannot dispose of it in a breath, as a mere play upon words. ‚ÄúMuch is reckoned higher than life itself by the living one.‚Äù Nietzsche says that to speak of the activity of life as a ‚Äústruggle for existence,‚Äù is to state the case inadequately. He warns us not to confound Malthus with nature. There is something more than th
U||is struggle between the organic beings on this earth; want, which is supposed to bring this struggle about, is not so common as is supposed; some other force must be operative. The Will to Power is this force, ‚Äúthe instinct of self-preservation is only one of the indirect and most frequent results thereof.‚Äù A certain lack of acumen in psychological questions and the condition of affairs in England at the time Darwin wrote, may both, according to Nietzsche, have induced the renowned naturalist to describe the forces of nature as he did in his ‚ÄúOrigin of Species‚Äù.
U||In verses 28, 29, and 30 of the second portion of this discourse we meet with a doctrine which, at first sight, seems to be merely ‚Äúle manoir a l‚Äôenvers,‚Äù indeed one English critic has actually said of Nietzsche, that ‚ÄúThus Spake Zarathustra‚Äù is no more than a compendium of modern views and maxims turned upside down. Examining these heterodox pronouncements a little more closely, however, we may possibly perceive their truth. Regarding good and evil as purely relative values, it stands to reason that what may be bad or evil in a given man, relative to a certain environment, may actually be good if not highly virtuous in him relative to a certain other environment. If this hypothetical man represent the ascending line of life‚Äîthat is to say, if he promise all that which is highest in a Graeco-Roman sense, then it is likely that he will be condemned as wicked if introduced into the society of men representing the opposite and descending line of life.
U||By depriving a man of his wickedness‚Äîmore particularly nowadays‚Äî therefore, one may unwittingly be doing violence to the greatest in him. It may be an outrage against his wholeness, just as the lopping-off of a leg would be. Fortunately, the natural so-called ‚Äúwickedness‚Äù of higher men has in a certain measure been able to resist this lopping process which successive slave-moralities have practised; but signs are not wanting which show that the noblest wickedness is fast vanishing from society‚Äîthe wickedness of courage and determination‚Äîand that Nietzsche had good reasons for crying: ‚ÄúAh, that (man‚Äôs) baddest is so very small! Ah, that his best is so very small. What is good? To be brave is good! It is the good war which halloweth every cause!‚Äù (see also par. 5, ‚ÄúHigher Man‚Äù).
U||Chapter LX. The Seven Seals.
U||This is a final paean which Zarathustra sings to Eternity and the marriage-ring of rings, the ring of the Eternal Recurrence.
U||...
U||PART IV.
U||In my opinion this part is Nietzsche‚Äôs open avowal that all his philosophy, together with all his hopes, enthusiastic outbursts, blasphemies, prolixities, and obscurities, were merely so many gifts laid at the feet of higher men. He had no desire to save the world. What he wished to determine was: Who is to be master of the world? This is a very different thing. He came to save higher men;‚Äîto give them that freedom by which, alone, they can develop and reach their zenith (see Note on Chapter LIV., end). It has been argued, and with considerable force, that no such philosophy is required by higher men, that, as a matter of fact, higher men, by virtue of their constitutions always, do stand Beyond Good and Evil, and never allow anything to stand in the way of their complete growth. Nietzsche, however, was evidently not so confident about this. He would probably have argued that we only see the successful cases. Being a great man himself, he was well aware of the dangers threatening greatness in our age. In
U|| ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù he writes: ‚ÄúThere are few pains so grievous as to have seen, divined, or experienced how an exceptional man has missed his way and deteriorated...‚Äù He knew ‚Äúfrom his painfullest recollections on what wretched obstacles promising developments of the highest rank have hitherto usually gone to pieces, broken down, sunk, and become contemptible.‚Äù Now in Part IV. we shall find that his strongest temptation to descend to the feeling of ‚Äúpity‚Äù for his contemporaries, is the ‚Äúcry for help‚Äù which he hears from the lips of the higher men exposed to the dreadful danger of their modern environment.
U||Chapter LXI. The Honey Sacrifice.
U||In the fourteenth verse of this discourse Nietzsche defines the solemn duty he imposed upon himself: ‚ÄúBecome what thou art.‚Äù Surely the criticism which has been directed against this maxim must all fall to the ground when it is remembered, once and for all, that Nietzsche‚Äôs teaching was never intended to be other than an esoteric one. ‚ÄúI am a law only for mine own,‚Äù he says emphatically, ‚ÄúI am not a law for all.‚Äù It is of the greatest importance to humanity that its highest individuals should be allowed to attain to their full development; for, only by means of its heroes can the human race be led forward step by step to higher and yet higher levels. ‚ÄúBecome what thou art‚Äù applied to all, of course, becomes a vicious maxim; it is to be hoped, however, that we may learn in time that the same action performed by a given number of men, loses its identity precisely that same number of times.‚Äî‚ÄúQuod licet Jovi, non licet bovi.‚Äù
U||At the last eight verses many readers may be tempted to laugh. In England we almost always laugh when a man takes himself seriously at anything save sport. And there is of course no reason why the reader should not be hilarious.‚ÄîA certain greatness is requisite, both in order to be sublime and to have reverence for the sublime. Nietzsche earnestly believed that the Zarathustra-kingdom‚Äîhis dynasty of a thousand years‚Äîwould one day come; if he had not believed it so earnestly, if every artist in fact had not believed so earnestly in his Hazar, whether of ten, fifteen, a hundred, or a thousand years, we should have lost all our higher men; they would have become pessimists, suicides, or merchants. If the minor poet and philosopher has made us shy of the prophetic seriousness which characterized an Isaiah or a Jeremiah, it is surely our loss and the minor poet‚Äôs gain.
U||Chapter LXII. The Cry of Distress.
U||We now meet with Zarathustra in extraordinary circumstances. He is confronted with Schopenhauer and tempted by the old Soothsayer to commit the sin of pity. ‚ÄúI have come that I may seduce thee to thy last sin!‚Äù says the Soothsayer to Zarathustra. It will be remembered that in Schopenhauer‚Äôs ethics, pity is elevated to the highest place among the virtues, and very consistently too, seeing that the Weltanschauung is a pessimistic one. Schopenhauer appeals to Nietzsche‚Äôs deepest and strongest sentiment‚Äîhis sympathy for higher men. ‚ÄúWhy dost thou conceal thyself?‚Äù he cries. ‚ÄúIt is THE HIGHER MAN that calleth for thee!‚Äù Zarathustra is almost overcome by the Soothsayer‚Äôs pleading, as he had been once already in the past, but he resists him step by step. At length he can withstand him no longer, and, on the plea that the higher man is on his ground and therefore under his protection, Zarathustra departs in search of him, leaving Schopenhauer‚Äîa higher man in Nietzsche‚Äôs opinion‚Äîin the cave 
U||as a guest.
U||Chapter LXIII. Talk with the Kings.
U||On his way Zarathustra meets two more higher men of his time; two kings cross his path. They are above the average modern type; for their instincts tell them what real ruling is, and they despise the mockery which they have been taught to call ‚ÄúReigning.‚Äù ‚ÄúWe ARE NOT the first men,‚Äù they say, ‚Äúand have nevertheless to STAND FOR them: of this imposture have we at last become weary and disgusted.‚Äù It is the kings who tell Zarathustra: ‚ÄúThere is no sorer misfortune in all human destiny than when the mighty of the earth are not also the first men. There everything becometh false and distorted and monstrous.‚Äù The kings are also asked by Zarathustra to accept the shelter of his cave, whereupon he proceeds on his way.
U||Chapter LXIV. The Leech.
U||Among the higher men whom Zarathustra wishes to save, is also the scientific specialist‚Äîthe man who honestly and scrupulously pursues his investigations, as Darwin did, in one department of knowledge. ‚ÄúI love him who liveth in order to know, and seeketh to know in order that the Superman may hereafter live. Thus seeketh he his own down-going.‚Äù ‚ÄúThe spiritually conscientious one,‚Äù he is called in this discourse. Zarathustra steps on him unawares, and the slave of science, bleeding from the violence he has done to himself by his self-imposed task, speaks proudly of his little sphere of knowledge‚Äîhis little hand‚Äôs breadth of ground on Zarathustra‚Äôs territory, philosophy. ‚ÄúWhere mine honesty ceaseth,‚Äù says the true scientific specialist, ‚Äúthere am I blind and want also to be blind. Where I want to know, however, there want I also to be honest‚Äînamely, severe, rigorous, restricted, cruel, and inexorable.‚Äù Zarathustra greatly respecting this man, invites him too to the cave, and then vanis
U||hes in answer to another cry for help.
U||Chapter LXV. The Magician.
U||The Magician is of course an artist, and Nietzsche‚Äôs intimate knowledge of perhaps the greatest artist of his age rendered the selection of Wagner, as the type in this discourse, almost inevitable. Most readers will be acquainted with the facts relating to Nietzsche‚Äôs and Wagner‚Äôs friendship and ultimate separation. As a boy and a youth Nietzsche had shown such a remarkable gift for music that it had been a question at one time whether he should not perhaps give up everything else in order to develop this gift, but he became a scholar notwithstanding, although he never entirely gave up composing, and playing the piano. While still in his teens, he became acquainted with Wagner‚Äôs music and grew passionately fond of it. Long before he met Wagner he must have idealised him in his mind to an extent which only a profoundly artistic nature could have been capable of. Nietzsche always had high ideals for humanity. If one were asked whether, throughout his many changes, there was yet one aim, one direction, 
U||and one hope to which he held fast, one would be forced to reply in the affirmative and declare that aim, direction, and hope to have been ‚Äúthe elevation of the type man.‚Äù Now, when Nietzsche met Wagner he was actually casting about for an incarnation of his dreams for the German people, and we have only to remember his youth (he was twenty-one when he was introduced to Wagner), his love of Wagner‚Äôs music, and the undoubted power of the great musician‚Äôs personality, in order to realise how very uncritical his attitude must have been in the first flood of his enthusiasm. Again, when the friendship ripened, we cannot well imagine Nietzsche, the younger man, being anything less than intoxicated by his senior‚Äôs attention and love, and we are therefore not surprised to find him pressing Wagner forward as the great Reformer and Saviour of mankind. ‚ÄúWagner in Bayreuth‚Äù (English Edition, 1909) gives us the best proof of Nietzsche‚Äôs infatuation, and although signs are not wanting in this essay which s
U||how how clearly and even cruelly he was sub-consciously ‚Äútaking stock‚Äù of his friend‚Äîeven then, the work is a record of what great love and admiration can do in the way of endowing the object of one‚Äôs affection with all the qualities and ideals that a fertile imagination can conceive.
U||When the blow came it was therefore all the more severe. Nietzsche at length realised that the friend of his fancy and the real Richard Wagner‚Äîthe composer of Parsifal‚Äîwere not one; the fact dawned upon him slowly; disappointment upon disappointment, revelation after revelation, ultimately brought it home to him, and though his best instincts were naturally opposed to it at first, the revulsion of feeling at last became too strong to be ignored, and Nietzsche was plunged into the blackest despair. Years after his break with Wagner, he wrote ‚ÄúThe Case of Wagner‚Äù, and ‚ÄúNietzsche contra Wagner‚Äù, and these works are with us to prove the sincerity and depth of his views on the man who was the greatest event of his life.
U||The poem in this discourse is, of course, reminiscent of Wagner‚Äôs own poetical manner, and it must be remembered that the whole was written subsequent to Nietzsche‚Äôs final break with his friend. The dialogue between Zarathustra and the Magician reveals pretty fully what it was that Nietzsche grew to loathe so intensely in Wagner,‚Äîviz., his pronounced histrionic tendencies, his dissembling powers, his inordinate vanity, his equivocalness, his falseness. ‚ÄúIt honoureth thee,‚Äù says Zarathustra, ‚Äúthat thou soughtest for greatness, but it betrayeth thee also. Thou art not great.‚Äù The Magician is nevertheless sent as a guest to Zarathustra‚Äôs cave; for, in his heart, Zarathustra believed until the end that the Magician was a higher man broken by modern values.
U||Chapter LXVI. Out of Service.
U||Zarathustra now meets the last pope, and, in a poetical form, we get Nietzsche‚Äôs description of the course Judaism and Christianity pursued before they reached their final break-up in Atheism, Agnosticism, and the like. The God of a strong, warlike race‚Äîthe God of Israel‚Äîis a jealous, revengeful God. He is a power that can be pictured and endured only by a hardy and courageous race, a race rich enough to sacrifice and to lose in sacrifice. The image of this God degenerates with the people that appropriate it, and gradually He becomes a God of love‚Äî‚Äúsoft and mellow,‚Äù a lower middle-class deity, who is ‚Äúpitiful.‚Äù He can no longer be a God who requires sacrifice, for we ourselves are no longer rich enough for that. The tables are therefore turned upon Him; HE must sacrifice to us. His pity becomes so great that he actually does sacrifice something to us‚ÄîHis only begotten Son. Such a process carried to its logical conclusions must ultimately end in His own destruction, and thus we find the pope
U|| declaring that God was one day suffocated by His all-too-great pity. What follows is clear enough. Zarathustra recognises another higher man in the ex-pope and sends him too as a guest to the cave.
U||Chapter LXVII. The Ugliest Man.
U||This discourse contains perhaps the boldest of Nietzsche‚Äôs suggestions concerning Atheism, as well as some extremely penetrating remarks upon the sentiment of pity. Zarathustra comes across the repulsive creature sitting on the wayside, and what does he do? He manifests the only correct feelings that can be manifested in the presence of any great misery‚Äîthat is to say, shame, reverence, embarrassment. Nietzsche detested the obtrusive and gushing pity that goes up to misery without a blush either on its cheek or in its heart‚Äîthe pity which is only another form of self-glorification. ‚ÄúThank God that I am not like thee!‚Äù‚Äîonly this self-glorifying sentiment can lend a well-constituted man the impudence to SHOW his pity for the cripple and the ill-constituted. In the presence of the ugliest man Nietzsche blushes,‚Äîhe blushes for his race; his own particular kind of altruism‚Äîthe altruism that might have prevented the existence of this man‚Äîstrikes him with all its force. He will have the world othe
U||rwise. He will have a world where one need not blush for one‚Äôs fellows‚Äîhence his appeal to us to love only our children‚Äôs land, the land undiscovered in the remotest sea.
U||Zarathustra calls the ugliest man the murderer of God! Certainly, this is one aspect of a certain kind of Atheism‚Äîthe Atheism of the man who reveres beauty to such an extent that his own ugliness, which outrages him, must be concealed from every eye lest it should not be respected as Zarathustra respected it. If there be a God, He too must be evaded. His pity must be foiled. But God is ubiquitous and omniscient. Therefore, for the really GREAT ugly man, He must not exist. ‚ÄúTheir pity IS it from which I flee away,‚Äù he says‚Äîthat is to say: ‚ÄúIt is from their want of reverence and lack of shame in presence of my great misery!‚Äù The ugliest man despises himself; but Zarathustra said in his Prologue: ‚ÄúI love the great despisers because they are the great adorers, and arrows of longing for the other shore.‚Äù He therefore honours the ugliest man: sees height in his self-contempt, and invites him to join the other higher men in the cave.
U||Chapter LXVIII. The Voluntary Beggar.
U||In this discourse, we undoubtedly have the ideal Buddhist, if not Gautama Buddha himself. Nietzsche had the greatest respect for Buddhism, and almost wherever he refers to it in his works, it is in terms of praise. He recognised that though Buddhism is undoubtedly a religion for decadents, its decadent values emanate from the higher and not, as in Christianity, from the lower grades of society. In Aphorism 20 of ‚ÄúThe Antichrist‚Äù, he compares it exhaustively with Christianity, and the result of his investigation is very much in favour of the older religion. Still, he recognised a most decided Buddhistic influence in Christ‚Äôs teaching, and the words in verses 29, 30, and 31 are very reminiscent of his views in regard to the Christian Savior.
U||The figure of Christ has been introduced often enough into fiction, and many scholars have undertaken to write His life according to their own lights, but few perhaps have ever attempted to present Him to us bereft of all those characteristics which a lack of the sense of harmony has attached to His person through the ages in which His doctrines have been taught. Now Nietzsche disagreed entirely with Renan‚Äôs view, that Christ was ‚Äúle grand maitre en ironie‚Äù; in Aphorism 31 of ‚ÄúThe Antichrist‚Äù, he says that he (Nietzsche) always purged his picture of the Humble Nazarene of all those bitter and spiteful outbursts which, in view of the struggle the first Christians went through, may very well have been added to the original character by Apologists and Sectarians who, at that time, could ill afford to consider nice psychological points, seeing that what they needed, above all, was a wrangling and abusive deity. These two conflicting halves in the character of the Christ of the Gospels, which no sound p
U||sychology can ever reconcile, Nietzsche always kept distinct in his own mind; he could not credit the same man with sentiments sometimes so noble and at other times so vulgar, and in presenting us with this new portrait of the Saviour, purged of all impurities, Nietzsche rendered military honours to a foe, which far exceed in worth all that His most ardent disciples have ever claimed for Him. In verse 26 we are vividly reminded of Herbert Spencer‚Äôs words ‚Äú‚ÄòLe mariage de convenance‚Äô is legalised prostitution.‚Äù
U||Chapter LXIX. The Shadow.
U||Here we have a description of that courageous and wayward spirit that literally haunts the footsteps of every great thinker and every great leader; sometimes with the result that it loses all aims, all hopes, and all trust in a definite goal. It is the case of the bravest and most broad-minded men of to-day. These literally shadow the most daring movements in the science and art of their generation; they completely lose their bearings and actually find themselves, in the end, without a way, a goal, or a home. ‚ÄúOn every surface have I already sat!...I become thin, I am almost equal to a shadow!‚Äù At last, in despair, such men do indeed cry out: ‚ÄúNothing is true; all is permitted,‚Äù and then they become mere wreckage. ‚ÄúToo much hath become clear unto me: now nothing mattereth to me any more. Nothing liveth any longer that I love,‚Äîhow should I still love myself! Have I still a goal? Where is MY home?‚Äù Zarathustra realises the danger threatening such a man. ‚ÄúThy danger is not small, thou free spiri
U||t and wanderer,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúThou hast had a bad day. See that a still worse evening doth not overtake thee!‚Äù The danger Zarathustra refers to is precisely this, that even a prison may seem a blessing to such a man. At least the bars keep him in a place of rest; a place of confinement, at its worst, is real. ‚ÄúBeware lest in the end a narrow faith capture thee,‚Äù says Zarathustra, ‚Äúfor now everything that is narrow and fixed seduceth and tempteth thee.‚Äù
U||Chapter LXX. Noontide.
U||At the noon of life Nietzsche said he entered the world; with him man came of age. We are now held responsible for our actions; our old guardians, the gods and demi-gods of our youth, the superstitions and fears of our childhood, withdraw; the field lies open before us; we lived through our morning with but one master‚Äîchance‚Äî; let us see to it that we MAKE our afternoon our own (see Note XLIX., Part III.).
U||Chapter LXXI. The Greeting.
U||Here I think I may claim that my contention in regard to the purpose and aim of the whole of Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy (as stated at the beginning of my Notes on Part IV.) is completely upheld. He fought for ‚Äúall who do not want to live, unless they learn again to HOPE‚Äîunless THEY learn (from him) the GREAT hope!‚Äù Zarathustra‚Äôs address to his guests shows clearly enough how he wished to help them: ‚ÄúI DO NOT TREAT MY WARRIORS INDULGENTLY,‚Äù he says: ‚Äúhow then could ye be fit for MY warfare?‚Äù He rebukes and spurns them, no word of love comes from his lips. Elsewhere he says a man should be a hard bed to his friend, thus alone can he be of use to him. Nietzsche would be a hard bed to higher men. He would make them harder; for, in order to be a law unto himself, man must possess the requisite hardness. ‚ÄúI wait for higher ones, stronger ones, more triumphant ones, merrier ones, for such as are built squarely in body and soul.‚Äù He says in par. 6 of ‚ÄúHigher Man‚Äù:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúYe higher men, think ye that I am here to put right what ye have put wrong? Or that I wished henceforth to make snugger couches for you sufferers? Or show you restless, miswandering, misclimbing ones new and easier footpaths?‚Äù
U||‚ÄúNay! Nay! Three times nay! Always more, always better ones of your type shall succumb‚Äîfor ye shall always have it worse and harder.‚Äù
U||Chapter LXXII. The Supper.
U||In the first seven verses of this discourse, I cannot help seeing a gentle allusion to Schopenhauer‚Äôs habits as a bon-vivant. For a pessimist, be it remembered, Schopenhauer led quite an extraordinary life. He ate well, loved well, played the flute well, and I believe he smoked the best cigars. What follows is clear enough.
U||Chapter LXXIII. The Higher Man. Par. 1.
U||Nietzsche admits, here, that at one time he had thought of appealing to the people, to the crowd in the market-place, but that he had ultimately to abandon the task. He bids higher men depart from the market-place.
U||Par. 3.
U||Here we are told quite plainly what class of men actually owe all their impulses and desires to the instinct of self-preservation. The struggle for existence is indeed the only spur in the case of such people. To them it matters not in what shape or condition man be preserved, provided only he survive. The transcendental maxim that ‚ÄúLife per se is precious‚Äù is the ruling maxim here.
U||Par. 4.
U||In the Note on Chapter LVII. (end) I speak of Nietzsche‚Äôs elevation of the virtue, Courage, to the highest place among the virtues. Here he tells higher men the class of courage he expects from them.
U||Pars. 5, 6.
U||These have already been referred to in the Notes on Chapters LVII. (end) and LXXI.
U||Par. 7.
U||I suggest that the last verse in this paragraph strongly confirms the view that Nietzsche‚Äôs teaching was always meant by him to be esoteric and for higher man alone.
U||Par. 9.
U||In the last verse, here, another shaft of light is thrown upon the Immaculate Perception or so-called ‚Äúpure objectivity‚Äù of the scientific mind. ‚ÄúFreedom from fever is still far from being knowledge.‚Äù Where a man‚Äôs emotions cease to accompany him in his investigations, he is not necessarily nearer the truth. Says Spencer, in the Preface to his Autobiography:‚Äî‚ÄúIn the genesis of a system of thought, the emotional nature is a large factor: perhaps as large a factor as the intellectual nature‚Äù (see pages 134, 141 of Vol. I., ‚ÄúThoughts out of Season‚Äù).
U||Pars. 10, 11.
U||When we approach Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy we must be prepared to be independent thinkers; in fact, the greatest virtue of his works is perhaps the subtlety with which they impose the obligation upon one of thinking alone, of scoring off one‚Äôs own bat, and of shifting intellectually for oneself.
U||Par. 13.
U||‚ÄúI am a railing alongside the torrent; whoever is able to grasp me, may grasp me! Your crutch, however, I am not.‚Äù These two paragraphs are an exhortation to higher men to become independent.
U||Par. 15.
U||Here Nietzsche perhaps exaggerates the importance of heredity. As, however, the question is by no means one on which we are all agreed, what he says is not without value.
U||A very important principle in Nietzsche‚Äôs philosophy is enunciated in the first verse of this paragraph. ‚ÄúThe higher its type, always the seldomer doth a thing succeed‚Äù (see page 82 of ‚ÄúBeyond Good and Evil‚Äù). Those who, like some political economists, talk in a business-like way about the terrific waste of human life and energy, deliberately overlook the fact that the waste most to be deplored usually occurs among higher individuals. Economy was never precisely one of nature‚Äôs leading principles. All this sentimental wailing over the larger proportion of failures than successes in human life, does not seem to take into account the fact that it is the rarest thing on earth for a highly organised being to attain to the fullest development and activity of all its functions, simply because it is so highly organised. The blind Will to Power in nature therefore stands in urgent need of direction by man.
U||Pars. 16, 17, 18, 19, 20.
U||These paragraphs deal with Nietzsche‚Äôs protest against the democratic seriousness (Pobelernst) of modern times. ‚ÄúAll good things laugh,‚Äù he says, and his final command to the higher men is, ‚ÄúLEARN, I pray you‚Äîto laugh.‚Äù All that is GOOD, in Nietzsche‚Äôs sense, is cheerful. To be able to crack a joke about one‚Äôs deepest feelings is the greatest test of their value. The man who does not laugh, like the man who does not make faces, is already a buffoon at heart.
U||‚ÄúWhat hath hitherto been the greatest sin here on earth? Was it not the word of him who said: ‚ÄòWoe unto them that laugh now!‚Äô Did he himself find no cause for laughter on the earth? Then he sought badly. A child even findeth cause for it.‚Äù
U||Chapter LXXIV. The Song of Melancholy.
U||After his address to the higher men, Zarathustra goes out into the open to recover himself. Meanwhile the magician (Wagner), seizing the opportunity in order to draw them all into his net once more, sings the Song of Melancholy.
U||Chapter LXXV. Science.
U||The only one to resist the ‚Äúmelancholy voluptuousness‚Äù of his art, is the spiritually conscientious one‚Äîthe scientific specialist of whom we read in the discourse entitled ‚ÄúThe Leech‚Äù. He takes the harp from the magician and cries for air, while reproving the musician in the style of ‚ÄúThe Case of Wagner‚Äù. When the magician retaliates by saying that the spiritually conscientious one could have understood little of his song, the latter replies: ‚ÄúThou praisest me in that thou separatest me from thyself.‚Äù The speech of the scientific man to his fellow higher men is well worth studying. By means of it, Nietzsche pays a high tribute to the honesty of the true specialist, while, in representing him as the only one who can resist the demoniacal influence of the magician‚Äôs music, he elevates him at a stroke, above all those present. Zarathustra and the spiritually conscientious one join issue at the end on the question of the proper place of ‚Äúfear‚Äù in man‚Äôs history, and Nietzsche avails hims
U||elf of the opportunity in order to restate his views concerning the relation of courage to humanity. It is precisely because courage has played the most important part in our development that he would not see it vanish from among our virtues to-day. ‚Äú...courage seemeth to me the entire primitive history of man.‚Äù
U||Chapter LXXVI. Among the Daughters of the Desert.
U||This tells its own tale.
U||Chapter LXXVII. The Awakening.
U||In this discourse, Nietzsche wishes to give his followers a warning. He thinks he has so far helped them that they have become convalescent, that new desires are awakened in them and that new hopes are in their arms and legs. But he mistakes the nature of the change. True, he has helped them, he has given them back what they most need, i.e., belief in believing‚Äîthe confidence in having confidence in something, but how do they use it? This belief in faith, if one can so express it without seeming tautological, has certainly been restored to them, and in the first flood of their enthusiasm they use it by bowing down and worshipping an ass! When writing this passage, Nietzsche was obviously thinking of the accusations which were levelled at the early Christians by their pagan contemporaries. It is well known that they were supposed not only to be eaters of human flesh but also ass-worshippers, and among the Roman graffiti, the most famous is the one found on the Palatino, showing a man worshipping a cross on 
U||which is suspended a figure with the head of an ass (see Minucius Felix, ‚ÄúOctavius‚Äù IX.; Tacitus, ‚ÄúHistoriae‚Äù v. 3; Tertullian, ‚ÄúApologia‚Äù, etc.). Nietzsche‚Äôs obvious moral, however, is that great scientists and thinkers, once they have reached the wall encircling scepticism and have thereby learned to recover their confidence in the act of believing, as such, usually manifest the change in their outlook by falling victims to the narrowest and most superstitious of creeds. So much for the introduction of the ass as an object of worship.
U||Now, with regard to the actual service and Ass-Festival, no reader who happens to be acquainted with the religious history of the Middle Ages will fail to see the allusion here to the asinaria festa which were by no means uncommon in France, Germany, and elsewhere in Europe during the thirteenth, fourteenth, and fifteenth centuries.
U||Chapter LXXVIII. The Ass-Festival.
U||At length, in the middle of their feast, Zarathustra bursts in upon them and rebukes them soundly. But he does not do so long; in the Ass-Festival, it suddenly occurs to him, that he is concerned with a ceremony that may not be without its purpose, as something foolish but necessary‚Äîa recreation for wise men. He is therefore highly pleased that the higher men have all blossomed forth; they therefore require new festivals,‚Äî‚ÄúA little valiant nonsense, some divine service and ass-festival, some old joyful Zarathustra fool, some blusterer to blow their souls bright.‚Äù
U||He tells them not to forget that night and the ass-festival, for ‚Äúsuch things only the convalescent devise! And should ye celebrate it again,‚Äù he concludes, ‚Äúdo it from love to yourselves, do it also from love to me! And in remembrance of ME!‚Äù
U||Chapter LXXIX. The Drunken Song.
U||It were the height of presumption to attempt to fix any particular interpretation of my own to the words of this song. With what has gone before, the reader, while reading it as poetry, should be able to seek and find his own meaning in it. The doctrine of the Eternal Recurrence appears for the last time here, in an art-form. Nietzsche lays stress upon the fact that all happiness, all delight, longs for repetitions, and just as a child cries ‚ÄúAgain! Again!‚Äù to the adult who happens to be amusing him; so the man who sees a meaning, and a joyful meaning, in existence must also cry ‚ÄúAgain!‚Äù and yet ‚ÄúAgain!‚Äù to all his life.
U||Chapter LXXX. The Sign.
U||In this discourse, Nietzsche disassociates himself finally from the higher men, and by the symbol of the lion, wishes to convey to us that he has won over and mastered the best and the most terrible in nature. That great power and tenderness are kin, was already his belief in 1875‚Äîeight years before he wrote this speech, and when the birds and the lion come to him, it is because he is the embodiment of the two qualities. All that is terrible and great in nature, the higher men are not yet prepared for; for they retreat horror-stricken into the cave when the lion springs at them; but Zarathustra makes not a move towards them. He was tempted to them on the previous day, he says, but ‚ÄúThat hath had its time! My suffering and my fellow-suffering,‚Äîwhat matter about them! Do I then strive after HAPPINESS? I strive after my work! Well! the lion hath come, my children are nigh. Zarathustra hath grown ripe. MY day beginneth: ARISE NOW, ARISE, THOU GREAT NOONDAY!‚Äù
U||...
U||The above I know to be open to much criticism. I shall be grateful to all those who will be kind enough to show me where and how I have gone wrong; but I should like to point out that, as they stand, I have not given to these Notes by any means their final form.
U||ANTHONY M. LUDOVICI.
U||London, February 1909.
